Air Jordan III Retro “Fire Red” - 2007 vs. 2022: Unfortunately, my 1988 Fire Red IIIs are LONG gone and I never picked up the 2013 version because I didn’t like them, but here’s a look at the 2007 vs. the 2022 releases. Besides the obvious Nike Air branding, there’s just so much they got right with the 2022s. The overall shape, the height of the elephant print around the toe, the shade of grey on the elephant print (2007 look lighter in pics, but is actually almost black in person), the fact that the leather wraps around the top of the tongue, hiding the lining, etc. Nothing will ever truly compare with any OG, but MAN… they got so much right with the 2022! #AJIII #AJ3 #FireRed3s.

#Nike is reportedly suing Japanese fashion brand #BAPE for "allegedly copying some of its most iconic footwear design‼️" Follow @DRIP for more updates‼️ According to Hypebeast, Nike claims that BAPE first introduced its first trademark-infringing footwear in the U.S. in 2005 and that for the 15 years, BAPE has had a presence in the American market, they have been infringing products. Sales of BAPE in the U.S. have reportedly been “sporadic” up until 2021, when the label, now owned by Hong Kong-based I.T. Ltd., “drastically increased the volume and scope of its infringement.” The lawsuit indicates, “BAPE’s copying is and always has been unacceptable to Nike, and because BAPE’s infringements have recently grown to become a significant danger to Nike’s rights, Nike must act now.” While both companies’ representatives have not yet commented on the issue, Nike has said that BAPE has “refused” to stop violating the trademark infringements when asked, leading to this lawsuit. Nike is hoping that BAPE will stop selling the shoes and pay a requested, unspecified amount of money for damages incurred. What do y'all think about this⁉️🤔

According to @espn, KD has officially become the third NBA player to sign a lifetime deal with the corporation. He now follows behind #MichaelJordan and #LeBronJames. Kevin first signed an endorsement deal with Nike as a rookie back in 2007, and now that the release of his 16th shoe is approaching, they have become locked in for life. 
____________________________________
KD spoke about the deal and said, "When I first signed with Nike, I couldn't have dreamed of how far we'd go in this partnership. We've done amazing work creatively and philanthropically. We've traveled the world together and built a business that will now last forever. I'm excited for the future and honored to be in rare company with this deal." (📸: @gettyimages)

The TSU Tigerbelles are known for the world records they broke, the style they pioneered, and the activism they inspired. Now, their legacy is the subject of an exhibit at the @ncrmuseum in Memphis, TN.

To celebrate the Tigerbelles, Nike commissioned an art installation—composed of over 20,000 track spikes—for display at the museum. Together with the museum, we also hosted multiple generations of Tigerbelles for a once-in-a-lifetime event to unveil the piece, bringing together 60-plus years of Tigerbelle history together in one room.

The exhibit will be on display for a limited time. Come visit the museum to witness history. Art fabricated by Gertrude East and Kevin Pierce.

Nostalgia 🤩

Rebecca Kilburn can’t easily find footwear for her son, 14-year-old Eric Jr., who stands 6 feet, 10 inches and wears a size 23 shoe.

Eric Jr. suffers from painful calluses, blisters and ingrown toenails caused by ill-fitting shoes. In the fall of 2022, the high school freshman sprained his ankle playing football because he didn’t have cleats. At the moment, Eric Jr. is wearing size 22 Nike sneakers. The sneakers had been made for a professional athlete, as Nike only goes up to a size 18. But the days of stretching shoes — and bandaging bleeding toes — are over.

Eric Jr.'s story went viral — and the family was inundated with people wanting to help. Under Armour and Puma will be creating custom shoes and cleats for Eric Jr., while Cat footwear wants to send him boots. A GoFundMe has raised more than $18,000 dollars. According to the fundraising page, the Kilburns plan to use the money towards future footwear and specialized sports equipment for Eric Jr.

Description:
Would you live in a 95-square-foot apartment? In Tokyo, some young people are choosing these extraordinarily small spaces, half the size of an average studio apartment.

Tokyo, the world’s most populous metropolitan area, has long been known for small accommodations. But these new apartments — known as three-tatami rooms, based on how many standard Japanese floor mats would cover the space — have taken that to an extreme.

Each unit has a 12-foot ceiling and a loft for sleeping. With efficient arranging, it is possible to squeeze in a washing machine, a fridge, a sofa and a work desk. The size works for the lifestyle of many young people in Japan, where it is not customary to host guests in homes.

The microapartments cost a few hundred dollars less than other studio apartments in similar areas, but they’re not exactly cheap. More affordable apartments can be found, though they are usually decades old. These shoe-box homes are new, stylish and situated near trendy locations in central Tokyo like Harajuku, Nakameguro and Shibuya, which are generally quite expensive. 

“I wouldn’t live anywhere else,” said Yugo Kinoshita, 19, a college student who gave up his Nike Dunk collection to live in one of the apartments.

Tap the link in our bio to see inside these tiny apartments. Photos by @norikohayashi_photo

Air Jordan III Retro “True Blue” - 2001 vs. 2009 vs. 2016: Back in 2001, the TB3 was the very first OG colorway of an Air Jordan to see the Jumpman replace the Nike branding. It was a really unpopular move at the time and was a sign of things to come for the next several years. Besides the branding, there were a couple of other differences. One being that the lining behind the tongue was now blue, instead of being red, as it was on the OG. The second was that the blue extended around the entire midsole, rather than stopping midway around the medial side. Regardless of the changes, the quality was good and it helped that we saw MJ himself wear a similar pair on court in 2003 (with copper accents, instead of red). The next TB3 release came in 2009 with what ended up being an international release only, which I was able to get living in Canada. This time around, they kept the Jumpman branding and the blue lining behind the tongue, but made it so the blue stopped midway around the medial side of the midsole like the OG. The shape was also decent and the height of the elephant print around the toe was lower than on the 2001, making it closer to the OG. But the paint on the midsoles cracked after a couple of wears and the materials felt pretty cheap overall. Then, in 2016, under the “Remastered” program, Brand Jordan brought the AJ 3 back after having kept them in the vault for 2 years. There was a big deal being made that they were also bringing back the Nike Air branding on the model. People were excited… until the actual release. Unfortunately, the Nike branding was the only decent part of that release. They also brought back the red lining behind the tongue for the first time since 1988, but the rest of the shoe was a mess. The shape was terrible, the shade of grey on the elephant print was bizarre, not to mention, the height of the elephant print around the toe was the highest we’d seen before or since. The leather was also strange. Overall, just a really disappointing release. With the recent Fire Red and upcoming White/Cement releases, it gives me hope that we will see the TB3 and Black/Cement 3s return properly. #TrueBlue3s.

We share the same values and passion for esports, and we believe that it can bring people together, inspire creativity, and create new career and business opportunities for everyone."

DJJayLew is a world-renowned DJ, music producer, and esports entrepreneur based in Las Vegas. He has worked with top artists and brands worldwide, including Jay-Z, Beyoncé, Nike, and Red Bull, and has been featured in major media outlets such as Forbes, Billboard, and ESPN. DJJayLew is also the founder and CEO of the esports organization, Team S!CK, which will compete in various games and leagues with aims to empower young gamers and minority creators. 

HipHop Gamer is a leading gaming journalist, influencer, and content creator based in New York City. He has interviewed and collaborated with top gaming personalities and companies, including Sony, Microsoft, and Nintendo, and has been featured in various media outlets such as CNN, MTV, and BET. Description:
Air Jordan IV “Black/Cement Grey” 1989-2019: If last week’s post confused people, I can only imagine what this one will do. As you can see, there have been several iterations of the black/cement Air Jordan IV released through the years. The closest we’ve gotten to this day, while still not identical to the OG, were the the very first retros back in 1999. After that, we moved into the Jumpman era. But not only did the branding change on the 2008 and 2012 releases, the entire shape completely changed. That’s when we got that “banana shape” that everyone knew and loved (sarcasm). The 2012 also saw the introduction of the ashy suede-like material. Not good. Both were not great versions in general, but of the two releases, the 2008 release that came in the Countdown Pack was the better one. Then, in 2019, Brand Jordan gave us what we wanted and brought the black/cement IVs back with Nike Air branding… BUT… the logo on the heel was completely off-centered. I’m not sure how or why that happened, but it did. So, while they did make some improvements from the previous two releases, in terms of overall shape (although still not quite right), shade of grey and better materials than on the 2012, etc. that off-centered Nike on the heels was enough to make a lot of people pass on the release, or if they did pick them up, they couldn’t get past it and they sold them. The 2019 release was also missing that grey edging that we saw on the 1989, 1999 and 2008 releases that added definition to the overall aesthetic. Overall, I didn’t mind the 2019 release, but there is definitely a lot of room for improvement. Hopefully we will see them return with the attention to detail that we’ve seen in recent years with the Air Jordan I, II and III. Now, let the fun begin in the comments! #1989 #1999 #2008 #2012 #2019 #AJIV #AJ4 #BlackCementNOTBred.

2006 vs. 2012 Air Jordan IV Retro “Military Blue”: There really aren’t a ton of differences between these two releases. The shape was ‘slightly’ improved on the 2012, whereas the 2006 has that crazy banana shape. Material was ‘a little’ better on the 2012 as well, but that’s not really saying much. I actually prefer the shade of blue on the 2006. I find the blue on the 2012 too bright. The slant of the netting is wrong on both. On thing that bothered me about the 2012 is that they made the color inside the air bubble blue, where it’s supposed to be white, like it is on the 2006. For some reason, that minor detail really annoys me 😆 What really needs to be said, though, is that we’ve never gotten a proper retro of the Military Blue IVs and it’s already been 10 years since the last time they retroed, so we are LONG overdue! I would LOVE to see these come back properly. Even though the 2020 Fire Red IVs weren’t perfect, I’d be happy if the Military Blues returned like those. Let’s hope we’ll see that happen sooner, rather than later! #AJIV #AJ4 #MilitaryBlue4s.

LAS VEGAS, May 28, 2023 - Ample Points, a Las Vegas funded start-up, announces the launch of their new $20 million dollar platform that allows users to earn money by watching advertisements and completing surveys. The platform, which is powered by patented technology, pays users up to $14.75 per hour in Ample Points that can be cashed out for real cash or towards purchases from thousands of vendors.

Djjaylew, a renowned DJ, has joined forces with Ample Points to endorse and onboard hundreds of new and existing local Las Vegas businesses onto the platform. Djjaylew met with Ample Points founder and CEO, Tony Singh, and co-founder Trevor Fraser, to discuss his role in the company.

In addition to onboarding businesses, Djjaylew will be the official DJ for Ample Points' multi-million dollar F1 party with hundreds of celebrities in November on the race track. He will also introduce the company's exclusive Super Bowl watch party with the biggest names in #sports at the Allegiant Stadium in Las Vegas.

Ample Points is the only platform in the world that pays users through Ample Points, which can be cashed out for real cash or used to purchase products from thousands of vendors such as Nike, Louis Vuitton, Gucci, and Hermes. Users can also use their points to acquire experiences such as F1 and Super Bowl tickets.

With Djjaylew's endorsement and influence, Ample Points is poised to revolutionize the way people earn money and make purchases. Users can start earning today without having to pay a penny.

Several women have taken to TikTok to join the “Burn Bra Challenge” to destroy their NIKE @nike sports bras after the sportswear giant hired transgender activist Dylan Mulvaney @dylanmulvaney to flog the company’s sports bras and leggings.

A TikTok user calling herself “chatterbox.mama,” and who also describes herself as a “southern mama,” posted her “Burn Bra Challenge” on Tuesday in which she is seen setting a NIKE women’s sports top on fire as she tells viewers that she is “sick and tired” of the company pushing women around, the New York Post reported. “All you real women out there – we are in the fight of all fights,” the woman said to her more than 140,000 followers.

“Since the 1960s, we have been fighting for the right to be women,” she added. “Nike, you should be ashamed of yourself.”

“NIKE, you should be ashamed of yourself. You chose a little boy with no breasts and some junk in his pants to represent real women,” she said, adding, “Nike, I am done with you.”

“I will never, ever buy a Nike product for as long as I live,” she said. “And there are millions and millions and millions of women just like me.”

She then challenged other women to “burn your Nike bras … as a way of showing our solidarity and how serious we are that we will be recognized.”

“We are the queens, your consumers hit you where it hurts, and that’s right in your pocket,” she said, concluding, “I challenge every real woman that is sick of this nonsense. It’s a great night to burn my Nike bras.”

“They’re pushing us around and we’re not doing anything about it!”

She then burned two bras next to her outdoor pool.

🟦🔵 Woke Backlash Escalates 🔵🟦 Veteran country music star Travis Tritt @realtravistritt announced Thursday he is no longer having Anheuser-Busch @anheuserbusch products on his touring hospitality rider. What’s more? Tritt says “I know many other artists who are doing the same.”

The move is his personal response to the brewer signing transgender activist, Joe Biden supporter, and TikTok star Dylan Mulvaney @dylanmulvaney to a lucrative endorsement deal that involved flogging its @budlight Bud Light beer.

Tritt used social media to make his decision public, saying “I will be deleting all Anheuser-Busch products from my tour hospitality rider. I know many other artists who are doing the same.” Tritt’s move came 24-hours after NIKE announced it too was embracing the endorsement of Mulvaney.

As Breitbart News reported, Oli London — whose life was turned upside down by transgenderism — posted Mulvaney’s recent video in which the latter reveals that he has entered into a deal to sell Nike’s women’s sports bra and leggings. Other entertainers have also shown their lack of support for the brewing giant and its choice of public endorsers.

Kid Rock has posted of video of himself shooting up cases of Bud Light in an apparent response to the beer brand’s hiring of Mulvaney as its new public face.

“Fuck Bud Light. And fuck Anheuser-Busch. Have a terrific day,” Kid Rock said in the video, flashing his middle finger. The makers of Bud Light have teamed up with male-to-female transgender Mulvaney to promote the beer brand on social media.

Anheuser-Busch has even put Mulvaney’s face on Bud Light cans to commemorate Mulvaney’s “365 days” of being a “girl.”

Mulvaney has posted at least two videos on social media to promote the product.

Just months after dropping their partnership with Kanye West over anti-Semitic remarks, WaPo reported that Adidas CEO Bjørn Gulden signaled this month that the company might not sell its Yeezy inventory.

The German sportswear giant is left with few good options for its Yeezy brand – a once-popular and lucrative segment of its business that was irrevocably tainted during West’s high-profile meltdown.

Adidas’ CEO is making no efforts to hide his predicament: He’s sitting on $1.3 billion (or 1.2 billion euros) worth of Yeezy product with no clear solution for how to get rid of it.

A final decision on what the company will do with the shoes is still months away, but options range from selling them without the Yeezy branding to literally burning them.

Adidas wouldn’t be the first company to torch its product. Several retailers, including Burberry, Coach, Victoria’s Secret, Louis Vuitton and Nike, have opted to destroy inventory that went unsold as a means of clearing surplus supply.

Experts warned the practice, while relatively commonplace, would be the “worst outcome” because it wouldn’t generate revenue and could spark backlash over waste and environmental costs.

At this point, Adidas has several options for what to do with the shoes, but none of them are all that appealing. It could sell them at a discount and without the label, like “zombie Yeezys,” as Nikic called them. But that could make it seem like Adidas is still profiting off an anti-Semite, he added. Other routes include liquidating the shoes through discount stores or selling them off by the pound.

Kanye West, who now goes by the name Ye, lost his Adidas deal and other partnerships after making the controversial anti-Semitic remarks. He also fell out of Forbes' billionaire list due to the scandal.

Air Jordan III Retro (White/Cement Grey) 1994 vs. 2003: Yes, I’m a sucker for punishment, BUT… I wanted to flip the script from what people reacted to with my 2007 vs. 2022 Fire Red comparison. Mainly, the fact that so many people were so upset that “Nike replaced Jordan’s logo.” It became very clear to me, as unbelievable as it sounds, that there is an entire era of sneakerheads who had no clue that the OG Air Jordans, the ones Michael Jordan himself wore, featured Nike Air branding. Much like my OG Fire Reds, my 1988 white/cement Air Jordan IIIs are LONG gone, but you can swipe to the last slide to see a photo of me wearing them back in 1988). On to the shoes: During Michael Jordan’s first retirement, Nike decided to re-release the first three models to commemorate his career. The first model to release in 1994 were the Air Jordan 3s. The news that this was happening was so exciting for me, because, I had destroyed my OGs, so the chance to own them again was something that I never could have imagined would happen, and I made the decision to keep them as pristine as possible, which I have to this day. While not identical to the 1988s, they are an incredible retro, complete with the original Nike Air branding. Then, 9 years later, as part of Brand Jordan’s portfolio, the white/cement 3s released once again. This time, however, they replaced the Nike Air branding with the Jumpman/Jordan branding. None of us who were around in 1988 were happy about this, as we wanted to have something as close to what MJ himself wore in 1988, and that included Nike branding. But we were forced to live with it. Aside from the branding, the shoes themselves saw several details change. The shade of grey was lighter, the elephant print was darker and the shade of red was different. They also made the leather on the tongue tumbled, whereas, it was smooth on the 1988 and 1994. Overall, the 2003 was a really nice retro, despite the Jumpman branding and subtle detail changes and I’m actually still able to wear them to this day. Having said all that, I am ridiculously excited to see how next year’s “Reimagined” white/cement 3s look! Now, let the fun begin in the comments!

The clock on the wall over my shoulder came from the garbage room in the apartment building my husband and I lived in together in NYC, before moving to the suburbs. I love it. The dark circles under my eyes are genetic - they’re always there no matter how rested I am, unless I’m wearing makeup. I don’t love the circles, but they’re part of me, and I do love myself. There is some shit on the counter behind me including a Dunkin’ Donuts bag from breakfast, and a Nike box with my daughter’s new sneakers in it. I could have cleared it off and gotten it “photo ready”, and I could have gotten myself “photo ready” too, but I didn’t. Later, I will get dressed and groomed and, at some point, I will clear off that counter, but for right now, this is what everything looks like. My image is not curated - I come as I am and I say what I’m inspired by in the moment. What you see here is what you get - no pretenses. I have talked about anxiety and the pain of my son’s cancer diagnosis and my gratitude for the little things (which are actually the big things) and I have danced and told MANY jokes about the sometimes back-breaking pressures of motherhood. If you’ve been following me for any length of time, you have seen both sides of me. Despite appearances I do care what people think, I suppose, because this is the “real” me rather than some insta-perfect representation of my life. I also care about other people a lot, and try to be a good person, even to internet strangers who sometimes say things that cut me a little. I’m getting better about leaving negative remarks in the dust, however, and am more and more sure of exactly who I am here each day. I like to make people laugh and/or feel validated, but my content is not for everyone, which is OK. I also appreciate the people who enjoy and support my content SO much. In many ways this Instagram community has given me a whole new purpose in life, and I’m so fucking excited about it. Thanks for being here. @bigtimeadulting

Description:
Waffle irons and the Willamette Valley. Patchouli and performance. This was the spirit of Eugene, Oregon in the 1970s. During this time, Nike was evolving and innovating rapidly which meant its graphic identity was too—especially on the t-shirt side of the hustle. Tees were the easiest way to communicate the brand’s rapidly developing identity. What’s most notable about these tees is that their bohemian, PNW-inspired look still influences much of the graphic work you still see in today’s designs.

Which one of these tees are you building a fit around? 

These original graphic tees were provided by the Department of Nike Archives.

Description:
A year after the death of Virgil Abloh — founder of Off-White, men’s wear designer of Louis Vuitton, Nike collaborator and artist — his widow, Shannon Abloh, sat down with The New York Times for her first interview.

Though her husband stayed in the public eye, Ms. Abloh preferred privacy and said she happily chose to be the “stable partner” for their family. Now, the spotlight has found her. After standing by politely as many expounded on Mr. Abloh’s life and work and what he would have wanted, she has decided it is time to define her husband’s legacy herself. “It belongs to me, it belongs to his children,” she said.

Last May, Ms. Abloh created Virgil Abloh Securities to unite his creative ventures; she is chief executive. This week, she will introduce a four-day festival during Miami Art Week that is designed to celebrate his life and open-source his ideas. Then, next spring, as president of the Virgil Abloh Foundation, she will host an inaugural summit of his closest collaborators, who will brainstorm ways to increase creative opportunities for the next generation of minority students. She is creating an archive. And she is ready to talk about what it all means.

“We never had the ‘this is the legacy that I want you to work toward’ discussion,” Ms. Abloh said. “But because I was with him for so long, I knew every inch of him. I knew every inch of his brain.”

Tap the link in our bio to read @vvfriedman’s full conversation with Shannon Abloh. Photo by @lelanief

#TSRUpdatez: Last month Brooklyn Nets point guard #KyrieIrving was accused of being antisemitic, which led to Nike suspending their relationship with him. Now it looks like it's officially a wrap for his relationship with the brand. 
____________________________________
On Monday, NBA insider Shams Charania shared that the company and Kyrie have decided to part ways, making him a sneaker-free agent. As previously reported, Nike co-founder Phil Knight spoke out after suspending their relationship with the NBA star and said, "Kyrie stepped over the line, it’s kind of that simple. He just made some statements we can’t abide by and that’s why we ended the relationship."
____________________________________
Kyrie has not formally spoken out since the news, however, he did share a tweet to Twitter, with a gif that reads, "There's nothing more priceless than being free." He also responded to Shams Charania’s tweet with a gif that reads, “Let the party begin.” (📸: @gettyimages)

Nike is finally taking a stand against BAPE, suing the Japanese fashion brand for allegedly copying some of its most iconic footwear designs.
-
Reuters reports that the Oregon-based shoe giant has filed a federal court lawsuit against A Bathing Ape for trademark infringement on the Nike Air Force 1, Air Jordan 1 and Nike Dunk. The lawsuit claims that “BAPE’s current footwear business revolves around copying Nike’s iconic designs.” The document also show cases five of BAPE’s top-selling footwear products — the BAPE STA, BAPE STA Mid, SK8 STA, COURT STA High and COURT STA — and now they are “near verbatim copies” of Nike’s aforementioned sneakers.
-
Nike claims that BAPE first introduced its first trademark-infringing footwear in the U.S. in 2005 and that for the 15 years, BAPE has had a presence in the American market, they have been infringing products. Sales of BAPE in the U.S. have reportedly been “sporadic” up until 2021, when the label, now owned by Hong Kong-based I.T. Ltd., “drastically increased the volume and scope of its infringement.” The lawsuit indicates, “BAPE’s copying is and always has been unacceptable to Nike, and because BAPE’s infringements have recently grown to become a significant danger to Nike’s rights, Nike must act now.”

@hypebeastkicks: Ukrainian concept designer @stanis.slav has created a pair of on point New Balance 990s.⁠

Starting life as a regular gray New Balance 990, Slav distresses the shoe within an inch of its inanimate life, crumbling the side-wall leather, rubbing away branding and the midsole, and expressing plenty of wear on the outsole. Now, the New Balance 990 sees its toe box extend way beyond typical proportions into a point. The result is something Martine Rose might approve of, à la the Martine Rose x Nike Shox MR 4, and overall it truly pushes the footwear boundaries into something uniquely conceptual and avant-garde.⁠

Description:
American rapper, Kanye West could lose his billionaire status after being dropped by Adidas amid growing backlash over his anti-Semitic rants.

The rapper's $220million annual deal with the German sports brand, which is worth $1.5billion in total, has been terminated after his controversial behaviour.

According to Forbes, West, 45, is set to lose his billionaire status after cutting ties with the sportswear giant – and is currently worth $2billion.

The rapper's wealth could plummet to below $1billion after the termination of the brand, which comes after several other lucrative deals have been dropped. 

Adidas announced that they would be terminating their partnership in a statement, with the sportswear maker having put its deal with Ye under review.

They claim that they made repeated efforts  earlier this month 'to privately resolve the situation.'

Adidas’ share price dropped more than 50 percent over the past six months and is expected to plunge even further in the wake of the announcement. 

In a statement Adidas said: 'Adidas does not tolerate antisemitism and any other sort of hate speech. 

'Ye's recent comments and actions have been unacceptable, hateful and dangerous, and they violate the company's values of diversity and inclusion, mutual respect and fairness.'

The company also claimed that cutting ties with the rapper is likely to have a 'negative impact of up to €250 million on the company's net income in 2022'. 

The partnership began in 2013, after he let a collaboration with Nike, and was expected to be a ten-year-long production.
Image Text: 武 KANYE WEST 'LOSES BILLIONAIRE STATUS' AFTER BEING DROPPED BY BRANDS FOR ANTISEMITIC REMARKS

From afar, it looks like your traditional AF1 but it's all about the details. Starting with the midsole, the words "Love You Forever" are embossed in cursive, while at the heel we see the signature NOCTA stars motif and the smallest detail of them all is near the toe, where the common stars are replaced with tiny hearts.⁠
⁠
The shoes are rumored to release on December 2 and will come paired with a special box featuring the "Love You Forever" script.⁠

Over the years, @nike has thoroughly evolved its options for personal training programs from the Nike+ App, Nike Run Club, Nike Training Club, and more.⁠

Designed for “everybody and every body,” the Swoosh is set to team up with @netflix to offer a combination of guidance with motivation as it assists athletes around the world in reaching fitness goals with a wide range of content.⁠
⁠
Netflix will host over 90 NTC workouts for all of its members, totaling over 223 million worldwide users. Packaged in programs, these workouts are designed for minimal to no equipment and cater to all fitness levels with 12 of Nike’s world-class trainers leading the exercises. These programs feature multiple episodes with over 30 hours of sessions coming to the platform. Expect content to be rolling in on December 30.⁠

Description:
New York City maintains no fewer than 40 official skate parks – miles and miles of poured concrete and obstacles designed specifically for skateboarding. But even with so many options, there’s just something about an empty plaza and a distracted security guard.

On a recent Sunday in Midtown, the New York Times photographer @heislerphoto followed a group of skaters that spanned two generations: Steve Rodriguez, his son, Shiki, and two of Shiki’s skate pals, Ari Misurelli and Jiro Platt. Their dads, Joe Misurelli and Jeremy Platt, were also in tow.

In his three decades skating the city's streets, Rodriguez — a respected athlete, business owner, skate park designer and activist — has probably seen as many social and cultural shifts as anyone. He was there when a tiny downtown skate shop named Supreme opened in 1994. (The brand was recently sold for $2.1 billion.) Rodriguez also recalls when the Brooklyn Banks — an area under the Brooklyn Bridge discovered by downtown skaters in the 1980s — closed in 2004 and again in 2010. Around that time, he won a grant from Nike and used the money to design and build a skate park nearby with help from the Tony Hawk Foundation. That park, now known to skaters as LES, one of New York’s most famous, and a popular meeting site for the dads on Sunday mornings.

Their sons know this history, some of which is the stuff of skate legend, like the Brooklyn Banks, which Mayor Eric Adams announced this week could be refurbished as part of a proposed $160 million development. And yet, the skaters admit, no one is drawn to skateboarding for its safe, well-designed spaces. For Shiki and his friends, improvising is key. 

“Skate spots are a hundred times better,” Shiki said. “You go to one spot and it’s not like anything at a park.”

Basketball legend #MichaelJordan reportedly requested #ViolaDavis to portray his mother in his upcoming movie “Air.”

According to reports, when director #BenAffleck met with Michael Jordan about his new film “Air,” which highlights the ballplayer’s historic sneaker deal with Nike, the basketball icon had one request.

Ben Affleck recently recalled what Michael Jordan requested of him and according to the filmmaker, Michael said,

“Viola Davis. That’s my mom.”

Reportedly, “Air” follows a key moment in Michael’s story of how his family and a group of executives at Nike revolutionized the business with the birth of the Air Jordan brand and the partnership between Nike and a then-rookie Michael. In addition to Viola Davis playing Michael’s mother, #DelorisJordan, Viola’s real-life husband, Julius Tennon, will star as Michael’s dad.

During a recent interveiw, Viola Davis talked about her latest role and reportedly shared,

“Mothers are the most important figures in anybody’s life, so I was very flattered and deeply moved to be asked to play Michael’s mother.”

The award-winning actress continued,

“I know Michael Jordan but didn’t know that Deloris brokered this deal to get him a huge stake in the shoe and in turn, protected her son’s legacy. I wanted to know more about this woman who had the strength and courage to fight for her son’s worth. For Deloris to have this insight and progressive vision, to stand her ground in the negotiation room — which I know can be the hardest part of the job — makes her an incredible woman…” Full story on #thejasminebrand.com
Image Text: the JASMINE BRAND Viola Davis Says She Was 'Very Flattered & Deeply Moved' When Michael Jordan Requested That She Portray His Mother In Upcoming Film 'Air' By Ariel Whitely 03/21/2023 the. Jasmine BRAND

Description:
In the new movie “Air,” Matt Damon plays Sonny Vaccaro, the former Nike executive who helped land an endorsement deal with Michael Jordan for Nike and gave him a cut of Air Jordan shoe profits. It makes the argument for letting the talent share in the moneymaking — which reflects exactly what its filmmakers, Damon and Ben Affleck, are trying to do in a new production venture. 

Damon and Affleck co-founded Artists Equity to make movies that earn more for their artistic talent. “Air” — directed by Affleck, who also plays the Nike co-founder and chief executive Phil Knight — was a deliberate choice for the company’s first project. “Thematically, it was on point in terms of what we’re trying to do with the new company,” Damon said in an interview with The New York Times.

Backed by $100 million from a private investment firm, the two movie makers started Artists Equity last year to restore to filmmakers a share of projects’ profits that had disappeared as Hollywood moved toward streaming and studios scaled back on the most generous deals. In Artists Equity’s view, turning filmmakers — whether stars or directors, cinematographers and editors — into something less like employees and more like financial partners will give them an incentive to make better movies more efficiently.

The real-life Vaccaro (second photo) embraced the moral of “Air” during a late-career shift from shoe-company veteran to advocate of college players’ rights.

Tap the link in our bio to learn just how closely the themes of “Air” mirror real life. Photos by @arielfish

⁠
Now, Nike has released a short video with Travis Scott and John McEnroe that shares the design’s return is “coming soon.” The campaign imagery begins with Scott and his Utopia briefcase standing next to McEnroe, with both wearing the aforementioned OG Mac Attack look. Afterwards, Scott is shown preparing a backhand stroke while wearing Utopia-themed Cactus Jack x Nike shorts.⁠

In a statement Tuesday, the sportswear maker said it "does not tolerate antisemitism and any other sort of hate speech" and said that his recent comments were "unacceptable, hateful and dangerous." -
Sales and production of his Yeezy branded products have stopped as well as payments to Ye and his companies. Adidas said it will take a €250 million hit ($246 million) to its fourth quarter sales.
-
Adidas has partnered with West since 2013, when the company signed his brand away from rival Nike. In 2016, Adidas expanded its relationship with the rapper, calling it "the most significant partnership ever created between a non-athlete and an athletic brand."

Description:
2001 vs. 2023 Air Jordan 3 Retro “Wizards” - Yes, Michael Jordan wore both colorways: So, this is a somewhat different comparison than I usually do. Normally, I compare different releases of the exact same colorway, but I got a few requests to compare these two releases, so here we go - Simply in terms of colorway and color blocking, these are obviously very similar. Simply replace the red accents with copper and BOOM, you’ve got a Wizards PE. It’s also important to note that what sets both releases apart from the 1988 original, aside from the obvious Jumpman branding (and copper on the 2023), is the fact that the blue wraps all the way around the midsole (see slide 4), whereas, it stops halfway on the medial side on the OG. As far as the detail differences between these two releases goes, you’ll first note a height difference, but that’s probably attributed to the fact that the 2001 is size 11.5 and the 2023 is size 11. The shades of blue are virtually identical. As far as the overall shape goes, the 2001 is obviously what MJ would have worn in 2001-2003, as that was the shape at the time. However, the 2023 is much closer to the shape of the 1988 original, so, had they gotten the shape right in 2001, that’s the shape MJ would have worn. Get it? 😆 The height of the elephant print around the toe is better on the 2023, in that it’s closer to what we would have seen in 1988. The lines on the elephant print itself on both the toe and heel are lighter, therefore, also much closer to what we would have seen in 1988, same with the overall shape of the toe box. You seeing a trend here? Ultimately, the overall shape and details of the elephant print on the 2023 is closer to what released in 1988, as opposed to the 2001. One small difference between the two, is that the lining on the 2023 is more of a nylon, as opposed to the usual felt/cotton material that the 2001 has. The 2023 colorway itself is based on an actual MJ PE that had never been released until now, and that is a VERY cool thing, in my opinion! Which do you prefer? #SideBySideSundays #2001 #2023 #TrueBlue3s #TB3 #WizardsPE.

Nike’s Banned “Maxsight” UV-blocking contact lenses (2006)

Bausch & Lomb and Nike developed the soft lenses, which are indicated for daily wear. They designed the lenses to protect athletes eyes from ultraviolet light. The lenses also enhance contrast in light conditions, helping athletes see fast-moving objects, such as baseballs, more clearly despite speed of travel. They were banned because they offered athletes an unfair advantage.

@hypebeastkicks: Two new colorways of @nike's Dunk Low Remastered, the newest entry in the Dunk line, have just surfaced. The silhouette is set to arrive in “Blue” and “White Gum.”⁠
⁠
Featuring a deconstructed aesthetic, the shoes are crafted with a mesh base, with smooth leather overlays and padded tongues. Exposed mesh is seen along the tongues to give the modified effect. The “White Gum” pair focuses on a cleaner aesthetic with an almost all-white build. As for its counterpart, the sneaker sees the upper dressed in two tones of blue. Completing the design are dissected tongues, splitting up the typical tongue tags.⁠
⁠
These are slated to drop via Nike and select retailers for $120 USD in Spring 2023.⁠

Description:
2006 vs. 2020 Air Jordan IV Retro “Fire Red”: @jumpman23 had released the “Laser” Fire Red IVs in 2005, which I did buy and still own, but left them out of this comparison because they were just too different. While the “MARS” IVs weren’t identical to the OG by any means, they were obviously much closer to them than the laser version and that was good enough for me at the time. Plus, I actually loved the tribute to MARS with the placement of his logo on the heels. I ended up doubling up on the 2006 release and have worn the heck out of one pair over the years. Jump to 2012 and we saw yet another release, but my 2006s were (and still are) very wearable and besides the removal of the “MARS” logo, the 2012s were basically the same. Actually, one change that was made was that they made the air bubble red inside. I didn’t like that. I preferred the “Mars” IVs, even with the logo on the heels, because they had a white air bubble, which was closer to the OG. So I passed on the 2012. I was so excited when they brought them back yet again in 2020, but this time, with Nike Air branding, proper slant on the netting and proper shade of red. While still not identical to the OGs, the 2020 release is a great version. Seeing that Nike Air on the heels really brings me back to when I rocked them to play ball in in the 10th grade in 1989 (see the last slide). As far as the other details of the 2020 that were and improvements from the 2006, besides the branding - the leather on the tongue of the 2020 wraps around the top like the OG, the netting is thicker like the OG, the toe is sleeker, less banana shaped than the 2006. Overall shape still needs work, but the 2020 was a great improvement compared to previous retro releases. Hope we’ll see the Military Blue IVs release sooner rather than later with some more improvements. #AJIV #AJ4.
•

⁠
The conceptual pair arrives completely mismatched, featuring a colorful patchwork assembly of Chiou's favorite characters and items from the Mario universe. Mystery Box graphics cover the toe box, character-related references decorate the heel counter, sawtoothed Bullet Bills are featured on the mudguard, and Toad’s polka-dotted mushroom hat is represented on the medial panels. Other subtle nods include Yoshi, Boomerang Flower, Wario, Princess Peach, Bowser, Donkey Kong, Princess Daisy, and Stone Block.⁠
Photo: Andrew Chiou

Description: Today I had a life changing experience filled with so much biblical history. We visited the Acropolis of Athens, a fortified citadel located on the top of a hill with four Temples. We saw historical landmarks including the Parthenon dedicated to Athena the Virgin in 447 BC, the Propylaea, the Temple of Athena Nike built in 431 BC, the Temple of the Maidens (Erechtheion), and the Odeon of Herodes Theater built in 174 AD. While many of the original buildings of the Acropolis were destroyed or repurposed, after Rome converted to Christianity in the 6th century AD many temples at the Acropolis became Christian churches. It was incredible and eye-opening to learn about the history of the city and gain so much biblical context!

Description:
Last night, when @SerenaWilliams walked onto the court at the #USOpen in Flushing Meadows, there were audible gasps. The crowd wasn’t just taking in the sheer presence of the 23-time Grand Slam tennis champion in the final tennis tournament of her career, but also Williams’s sparkling and shimmering look, which was completely covered in crystals.

The September cover star designed this custom black Nike set herself. The look was inspired by dresses worn by figure skaters and featured a gem-encrusted bodice with starry details evoking the night sky over the Arthur Ashe Stadium stadium and a tulle skirt with six layers to symbolize her previous US Open wins.

Tap the link in our bio for even more details about the stunning look.

@hypbeastkicks: @nike and @xxxibgdrgn are joining forces once again to roll out a @peaceminusonedotcom x Nike Kwando 1 “Panda” colorway. The upcoming pair features a tuxedo-esque arrangement as the base is dialed to a crisp white while leather overlays, Swooshes, thick lace shrouds, bottoms, and wing tip toe boxes contrast with a solid black. ⁠
⁠
Elsewhere, branding is carried over from the duo’s first release with a Nike Sportswear logo on the right shoe and a PEACEMINUSONE on the left. While no release date has been announced yet, it’s expected that the pair will drop in the coming months for $180 USD. ⁠

⬛️◼️ The backlash against extreme-Left NIKE @nike has begun.◼️⬛️ NIKE @nike told customers to “be kind, be inclusive” in response to the brewing backlash over the company selecting transgender Dylan Mulvaney @dylanmulvaney as brand ambassador to sell women’s attire.

In a pinned comment to one of NIKE’s Instagram posts, the company responded to the barrage of people announcing they would be abandoning the brand for good.

“You are an essential component to the success of your community! We welcome comments that contribute to a positive and constructive discussion: Be kind. Be inclusive. Encourage each other. Hate speech, bullying, or other behaviors that are not in the spirit of a diverse and inclusive community will be deleted,” NIKE said.

As Breitbart News reported this week, NIKE Women selected Dylan Mulvaney to sell women’s sports bras and leggings despite being a man.

“Home for a moment and leaning into cozy workout wear life with @nikewomen ‘s newest Zenvy leggings and Alate bra! They’re so comfortable and buttery soft, perfect for workouts and everyday wear! #feelyourall #teamnike #nikepartner,” Mulvaney said when announcing the new deal on Instagram. Customers responded by vowing to boycott the sports apparel giant and said the selection of Dylan Mulvaney contributes to the erasure of women. Female athletes are also weighing in on the situation.

“It’s so frustrating. We take two steps forward with World Athletics and Swim England protecting women’s sport and then Nike does this,” Olympic swimmer Sharron Davies told Dan Wootton Tonight on GB News.

“The ad feels like a parody of what women are. In the past, it was always seen as an insult to say ‘run like a girl,’ and here we’ve got someone behaving in a way that’s very unsporty and very unathletic. And it’s so frustrating when only 1% of the USA sponsorship dollar goes to females in sport. That Nike would do this feels like a kick in the teeth,” she added.

@hypebeastkicks: ⁠When @tomsachs and @nike produced the General Purpose Shoe through their collaborative NikeCraft label, Sachs made it clear that his goal with the silhouette was accessibility. ⁠
⁠
Tom Sachs implored consumers not to pay resale for the GPS as it would be “restocked” and “perennial,” and ran campaigns that playfully derided his own design as “boring,” while also stating that creativity was “the enemy.” Sachs jumped through a lot of hoops to ensure that the GPS was a shoe of the people, and his biggest effort yet was stocking large quantities of it at @kohls.⁠

#PhilKnight co-founder of #Nike  and his wife, Penny, pledged a multi-million dollar donation to his hometown of Portland, Oregon to rebuild the city's Albina area. Nike's longtime headquarters is in Beaverton, Oregon, a suburb of Portland.

Located in the north and northeast sections of Portland, Albina is a historically Black community whose locals have been displaced during its more than century-long history through redlining and discriminatory housing practices. Now, Knight has pledged $400 million to assist in rebuilding the area's Black comm
unity for existing and future generations.

Nike SB Dunk Low “Blue Raspberry”

Another “tasty” model from the Nike SB Dunk “Fruity Pack” collection.

At the heart of the model is leather, complemented by suede overlays and “shaggy” swoosh.

All Fruity Pack shades have patches on the inside of the tongues with images of the respective fruits.
Here, on the tongue, a blackberry with a relaxed expression is depicted.

The set includes two colors of laces to match the top: lighter blue and deep blue.

The collection, in addition to the “Blue Raspberry” model, also includes the colors: Pineapple, and Green Apple, Cherry.

@hypebeastkicks: ⁠During @kanyewest's time with @nike, it appears that he had exclusive pairs made for him and his closest friends, one being this Air Jordan 6 “Donda West” colorway that was crafted to honor his mother who passed away in 2007. ⁠
⁠
The pair sees intricate lasered roses that grace the overlays, heels, and toe boxes. Actual rose graphics are embroidered on the heels and tongues, while Donda’s moniker and lyrics from Ye’s tune “Roses” are laid down on the insoles. From there, muted red accents dress the lace toggles, tongues, heel counters, and midsoles.⁠
⁠
Only a handful of pairs were made and @christiesinc is currently auctioning off a size 12.⁠

Description:
🪡 LV Boro Dunks 🥀 for @dermotkennedy
Inspired by Virgil Abloh 🕊️. Specifically the destroyed denim jacket/jeans from Louis Vuitton’s FW22, Virgil’s final collection that he designed with LV before his passing. When I saw the pieces used the boro technique, I knew I had to make my own custom based off them. ✨

Base shoe was a pair of Marina Blue Nike Dunks. I hand stitched stacked sashiko stitches on the toe box and side panels, dyed/bleached the fabrics to get the right color match, distressed the floral patterns to emulate the referenced pieces, used my leather sewing machine to stitch the uppers, aged the midsoles, and finished with cream laces. Each swoosh features a different color flower. 🌹🌼🌺 #virgilwashere

@hypebeastkicks: Toward the end of 2022, events between @nike and @stockx escalated as the two companies engaged in an ongoing lawsuit. The Swoosh sued the reseller platform for allegedly selling counterfeit shoes and having an unreliable authentication process. According to reports, the reseller bought many University Blue, Mocha, and Hyper Royal Jordan 1s on StockX when the market price had dropped with the intent of holding and flipping later. ⁠

The Brown Files: Part III

In September last year,  I introduced Tiffany to the legendary Wilson Smith III @shoeitecture , the first black designer in the footwear industry. Wilson is the mind behind the iconic Air More Uptempo, a shoe I vividly remember as a kid for its distinct “AIR” text on the sides.  The event was to commemorate the release of a special colorway of the shoe to honor the legendary designer. He was blown away when I told him the the story of how we met 😁.

Wilson just might be one of the nicest, most kind hearted, positive people I have ever met.  His energy is infectious. Without Wilson there is no “Me” at a company like Nike. 

It’s important to acknowledge the people that paved the way for the future generations. With that being said, thank you Wilson!!

Kaig Lightner founded the Portland Community Football Club to give local youth an inexpensive chance to play. When he came out as transgender, they gave him a place to belong.

During Lightner’s adolescence, he recalls a paralyzing fear that began around age 4 that he was a boy stuck in a girl’s body. Amid bullying, sports became a refuge. “Sports kept me alive,” he said.

Lightner took a job as an instructor for after-school programs in the working-class outskirts of Portland, Oregon, home to many of the city’s immigrants from Africa, Mexico, Central and South America and Asia. He noticed that the abundant sports opportunities in the city’s wealthier communities barely existed for these kids. After a year of cobbling together seed money, Lightner formed the Portland Community Football Club in 2013 with grant funding and donated equipment from Nike. The club was a rarity because everybody had a place. Nobody was cut, and the price was affordable and negotiable. 

Lightner was open about being a transgender man to everyone in his life except his players and their families, and the dissonance ate at him. So finally in 2017, he gathered every player for a chat before practice. The response was acceptance. One player chuckled nervously but walked to Lightner for a hug. No one left.

@hypeart: After transforming @nike boxes into functional furniture with his “The Pattern Is the Pattern” series, South Korea-based artist @gyuhan_lee has returned with his latest playful project. This time around, Lee has upcycled @mcdonalds paper bags into lighting sculptures in another exploration of consumer culture.⁠
⁠
Dubbed "Tokyo Edition: McDonald’s Paper Bag Lamp 12-1 2022" and "Tokyo Edition: McDonald’s Paper Bag Lamp 12-2 2022," Gyuhan Lee sourced the familiar carrier bags at @narita.airport_official during a recent trip to Tokyo.⁠
⁠
The iconic golden arches have been reinterpreted in the works as a repetitive pattern. Additionally, the process created an interesting interaction between manufactured and artisanal handcrafting. Replicating the effect of Hanji (traditional Korean paper), the recycled paper bag sections are applied to a metal frame to create striking geometric forms that tie together to function as a lamp.⁠
⁠
Swipe through for a closer look.⁠
Photo: Gyuhan Lee

The Jordan brand was created in 1984 by Nike for MJ who - just entered the league - was looking for sponsors who could accompany him in his early years in the NBA.

 He didn't even want to sign with them, he liked Adidas.  But his mother insisted that he at least go to the meeting that the company had prepared for him and, once there, the parties agreed.

 From 1984 to 1987 the products in his line continued to be 'signed' with the swoosh, the iconic Nike mustache, but both MJ and the company wanted to find something that represented him more.

 Something that just looking at him made you think of Michal Jordan, the man who started to fly when he jumped.

 He didn't need to say more.
 The rest is history. #jordanbrand ✈️

I remember it like it was yesterday. This was the first day I was ever truly around Kobe away from the court. Kob had an aura about him- like very few people I’ve ever met or seen. Anyone that was ever around him knows what I’m talking about. In a room full of stars, he was the star that stood out. Even they were in awe…I saw it this day first hand. Let me paint the picture. We’re in the same waiting area for players and participants, he’s there before me, I walk in and he’s like “Mal what’s up “ I smile like a kid like “ what’s up Kob” from that moment on, we’re just chopping it up about life, hoop, family. Family was EVERYTHING to him. He was just so normal. Btw, his family was at a spot he always could watch them even though he was very present in the conversation with the fellas. They never left his sight.
Fast forward, while the softball game is going on, I’m getting more comfortable talking to him, and i had a pro am game after the softball game that we were at. Anytime someone is in Seattle, the city assumes I can get them to pro am. So the pressure was on me that day lol!! And I was so nervous to ask, but something inside me this is now or never. And it just comes out..I shoot my shot, “Kob, will you stop by my game before you leave town” he’s like “you playing” I said “ yea” he said “ I’m coming” There’s a guy there from Nike ( who’ll remain nameless ha) that was like “no we gotta get back to LA” Kob said” No, I’m going to watch Jamal play” I was BLOWN AWAY!! Him and his family had every reason to say, “ we can’t make it, too last min” and I would’ve understood!! But they made time. And I was so shocked. My respect for them went to a whole nother level. He comes on the court to wave to everyone, sunglasses on inside, as cool as ever lol. It’s pandemonium . It’s Kobe right here in front of us. Him and his family leave, and we stay in touch from there on. Three years ago today, all of our lives changed forever. We all get sad when we think about it, but the inspiration Kob and GiGi have left, will always make us push to be the best versions of ourselves…And that will live on forever. 🙏🏾

Air Jordan III Retro (Black/Cement Grey) - 2001 vs. 2008 (CDP) vs. 2018: Unfortunately, I never owned the black/cements in 1988. I was 14-15 at the time, so I was really lucky to have owned the WC and FR 3s in 1988. When the white and black/cements re-released in 1994, I was a broke college student, so I had to pick one and I decided to go with the colorway I had when I had in high school and had destroyed playing ball, which was the WC3s. I actually came across the 1994 BC3s for $50 in NYC in 1996, but once again, I couldn’t afford it, and I had to pass. So, it wasn’t until they re-released for the second time in 2001, when I had a decent paying job that I was finally able to grab my first pair of black/cement 3s. The 2001s are a great release, but they definitely are different from the 1988 and even the 1994. The 2001, however, the last BC3 release to feature Nike branding. The 2008, which were included with the AJ XX as part of the Countdown Pack series, are “okay” but are not great. Obviously, this was the first time we had seen the BC3s with Jumpman branding, instead of Nike branding, which was the most obvious change. But the leather was also much cheaper feeling and the paint on the midsoles cracked really quickly. There was a 2011 retro as well, but I skipped those because they were too similar to the 2008s. So, it was another 10 years before I picked up another pair of BC3s. This time, they brought back the original Nike branding for the first time since 2001. They also made an improvement on the Nike Air logo on the heels. The logo on the heels of the 1994 and 2001 releases were just black lettering that was painted white on the surface, whereas, the 1988 was actually white lettering. With the 2018, they brought back the white lettering. But besides that, the shape isn’t great, which is probably my biggest issue with them. No retro, including the 1994 and 2001, got the height of the elephant print around the toe right. The shade of grey was closer to the OG on the 1994, as were the lines on the elephant print, which was more subtle like the OG. Looking forward to seeing the BC3s return with the OG details like we’ve seen with the recent Fire Red 3s!

Description:
BIKE AIR. For the design inspiration, we tapped into my upbringing and hometown of Queens, NY. The Air Ship story is essential because it’s the first sneaker MJ wore when he came into the league. This sneaker is about origins and proving yourself. I’ve had to prove myself my entire career, justify my value to the sport of BMX, not be afraid to go against the grain, and create a new blueprint. I’m grateful for everything thus far, but I have much further to GO, and I will continue to turn up because I LOVE this sh*t. 

Flipping the classic NIKE AIR logo to BIKE AIR is crazy on so many levels, but most importantly, it’s a testament to my bike riding, vision, hard work, and dedication to my goals. My desires have been, remains, and will always be to put my Dreams In Motion. I started something special in my grandma’s driveway all those years ago and will continue pushing it forward. Salute to my @jumpman23 family for making this happen. @go.intl

Neigh Balance or Air Horse 1s? 👟🐴
 
A shoe artist, from Lexington in the US, has created designer trainers for horses.
 
Marcus Floyd uses a medical horse shoe as a base for his designs, then customises them using trainers by Nike, New Balance and Adidas for inspiration.
 
A custom shoe starts at $1,200 (£1,070) per hoof.
 
The city of Lexington in Kentucky has been dubbed the “horse capital of the world” and Marcus said it was time to change the “boring” and “traditional” horseshoe.
 
Tap the link in our bio read about the creative process behind the designs.

#Socialites, get into this! Cops have flooded the home of our Bajan queen Rihanna! According to TMZ, law enforcement officials reported that a man walked up to Rihanna’s home on Thursday (March 23), after traveling from South Carolina. 
___________________________________________________ 
Once the man, dressed in a red Nike hoodie and dark pants, arrived to the singer’s home — where she is raising a young family and is currently with child — he was immediately confronted by her security team. Sources told the outlet that the man revealed his motives for popping up at Rih’s house unannounced. Apparently, he intended on proposing to the “Diamonds” singer. However, his fairytale was quickly re-written after Rih’s security team apprehended him and called the cops to take him away. 
___________________________________________________ 
When officials with the local police department arrived to Rih’s home, they quickly put the man in handcuffs and escorted him to a patrol car, where they, reportedly, “had a serious chat about his intentions.” Law enforcement officials told the outlet that the man had not committed any serious crimes or broken any laws, so he was simply escorted away, and told that he could not return to the property again. Now, this is not the first time Rihanna has had an uninvited visitor pop up at her home before. Back in 2018, a man named Eduardo Leon was arrested after making his way inside of Rih’s home in the Los Angeles, CA area. It was reported that while Rih was out of town, Leon had allegedly been inside of the home for at least one day before he was busted lounging around. Allegedly, he told police that he was there because he had planned on having sex with the singer.

Founded in 2000, @skatelikeagirl’s goal of bringing together non-traditional skateboarders hasn’t changed much over the past 22 years. Hosting programs and events in Seattle, Portland, and the Bay Area, Skate Like a Girl continues to create space for people historically excluded or who faced barriers to access.

Beyond these three chapter cities, Skate Like a Girl empowers a global audience through the Skateboarding Inclusivity Cooperative (SIC), ad-free video skateboarding tutorial content, and the multi-day community event, Wheels of Fortune, to name a few.
 
Nike SB is proud to introduce the Skate Like a Girl capsule collection, including SB Dunk Low, hoodie, crewneck, and t-shirt, available Saturday, October 15 in select skate shops and Tuesday, October 18 in SNKRS.

@hypebeastkicks: According to reports, sportswear brands like @nike and @adidas are expected to significantly reduce production starting next year. The report notes that major names in the footwear industry have notified their manufacturing companies that they will be reducing order volumes by 30-40 percent starting in the summer of 2023. ⁠
⁠
It’s been reported that the main reason for the decline is the ongoing hindrances caused by the pandemic in China which serves as a major sales market for brands along with the withdrawal of retail locations in Russia. Industry insiders have additionally noted that the trend will continue to affect production until Winter 2023. For more details, head to the link in bio. ⁠

Ben Affleck is many things: Batman, sad man, sad Grammys man, Dunkin fan. In the trailer for Air, he adds Phil Knight to that list.⁠
⁠
Knight is the billionaire co-founder of Nike and he figures deeply into the plot of @airmovie. Directed by and starring Affleck, his pal Matt Damon, Marlon Wayans, Viola Davis, and Jason Bateman, the biopic centers around Nike's quest to sign Michael Jordan back in the early '80s.⁠
⁠
A few Jordan sketches appear in the trailer, which gives an overview to the quest that Damon undertakes to recruit Jordan to Nike.⁠
⁠
We see everything from the OG Cortez to a rough sketch of the inimitable Jumpman logo in the process.⁠
⁠
It's not actually clear whether there's any involvement from Nike itself in the movie, though one has to assume that the Swoosh would've had to clear all of the copyrighted imagery seen in the film. AIR's April release would actually be a great time to retro a coveted Jordan 1, actually (are Chicagos coming back?!?).⁠
⁠
Air premieres April 5. ⁠
⁠
Hit the link in bio to watch the trailer.⁠
⁠
📷: Air Movie

Rhea Bullos, an 11-year-old track athlete from the Philippines, won three gold medals in the 400-meter, 800-meter, and 1,500-meter competitions at the Iloilo Schools Sports Council Meet.
+
After her stunning wins, she was sitting and watching the rest of the race when someone noticed her feet. Rhea was wearing ‘shoes’ made out of bandages. She had even added a Nike logo on them.
+
“I’m glad she won,” her trainer Predirick Valenzuela said in an interview. “She worked hard to train. They only get tired when training because they don’t have shoes.”
+
The word spread on social media and many people offered to sponsor the Rhea. She received new shoes, socks and a sports bag from a shoe store in local mall SM City. 
--

According to reports, sportswear brands like Nike and Adidas are expected to significantly reduce production starting next year. The reports note that major names in the athletic footwear industry have notified their manufacturing companies that they will be reducing order volumes by 30-40 percent starting Summer 2023. Industry insiders are noting that the trend will continue to affect production until Winter 2023, meaning we could see a decline in releases until the Summer 2024 season.
-
The main reason for the decline in volume is the ongoing hindrances caused by the COVID-19 pandemic in China, a major sales market for brands, and the continued withdrawal of retail locations in Russia. Additionally, despite the growth of the retail market in North America and Europe this past year, a significant drop is expected for next year.
-
The decline is already being felt in factories across Vietnam and Indonesia, average operation rates used to sit around 82-84 percent, but have now fallen to 61 percent.

Mbappé en mode capitaine 💪

C'est officiel, Kylian Mbappé est le nouveau capitaine de l'équipe de France, prenant la suite d'Hugo Lloris qui a pris sa retraite internationale après le mondial. Avant même sa nomination, Kyks a comme assumé sa nouvelle responsabilité avec un look d'arrivée à Clairefontaine sobre et élégant, centré sur le bleu marine entre manteau mi-long, col roulé ou jean brut, le tout parachevé par une Blazer Mid simple et efficace 🌟

Si on fait le parallèle entre cette tenue et son nouveau statut, c'est qu'elle tranche avec les outfits auxquels le natif de Bondy nous avait habitués à ses venues au centre d'entraînement des Bleus. Mbappé versait en effet quasi-exclusivement dans le sportswear, et des total looks de son sponsor Nike. Seule chose qui ne bouge pas en tout cas : la sneaker ! 

Que pensez-vous du style de Kylian Mbappé ? Vous validez cette évolution vers le vestiaire formel, ou vous préférez ses tenues plus street ?

@hypebeastkicks: @nike has just presented its latest installment to its ISPA line, the Mindbody — an all-new design that looks like it has been molded from trash.⁠
⁠
The Swoosh has applied the four ISPA pillars of Improvise, Scavenge, Protect, and Adapt to give the sneaker an aged look. Additionally, the shoe's components have been welded together to emphasize an up-cycled appearance. Coming in various shades of brown, the silhouette's upper is constructed with Flyknit and is interlaced with laces that resemble a wired aesthetic. A chunky rubber outsole is also included with an unevenly-detailed platform.⁠
⁠
Expect the pair to release online via Nike in the coming weeks.⁠
Photo: Nike⁠

Description:
Megan Thee Stallion just made history by becoming the first Black woman on the cover of Forbes’ ’30 under 30’ issue. 

‘It’s really hard to be the first something in 2022, so ah!’ Megan told Forbes. 

In addition to being one of the biggest stars in the music industry and having lucrative deals with companies such as Netflix, Nike, and Popeyes, the Grammy-winning hip-hop artist also made headlines this year as an advocate for mental health. In her newest album, ‘Traumatize,’ Megan opens up about her experiences with topics such as mental illness and grief. 

When discussing the album, Megan told Forbes, ‘It made me feel happy that the time I did decide to be vulnerable and talk about something I was going through, it was one of the favorites from all of my fans... like it’s ok to not be ok and it’s ok to tell y’all I’m not ok.’

In September, Megan launched a website called ‘Bad Bitches Have Bad Days Too,’ which helps connect people with mental health resources, such as therapy and hotlines for drug abuse, suicide, and LGBTQ+ support. 

‘I want to be bigger than just my music,’ Megan added. ‘I’m trying to really build something.’

Description:
Travis Scott, tout oublié, tout pardonné ? 🤔
 
  C'était il y a à peine un an, mais cela paraît déjà loin. Après le drame du festival Astroworld qu'il organisait, où des mouvements de foule avaient fait 10 morts et des milliers de blessés, Travis Scott était dans la tourmente. 
 
  Visé par des centaines de plaintes lui réclamant des milliards de dollars de dommages, critiqué sur les réseaux sociaux, déprogrammé par des festivals et lâché par des sponsors, La Flame était descendu de son piédestal. Mais le voilà déjà de retour au premier plan, et même réinstallé sur son fauteuil de roi de la hype ! 👑
 
  Une réhabilitation record qui tient d'une fine stratégie, au terme de laquelle le rappeur a pu délivrer ses collections avec Dior ou Nike, apparaissant même plus bankable que jamais. Il a aussi repris les concerts comme tête d'affiche, tandis que son projet Utopia semble en passe de se concrétiser. Quid des plaintes déposées à son encontre ? 
 
  L'enquête de la police du Texas et du FBI n'a pas livré ses conclusions, alors la justice est en attente... Pensez-vous que la tragédie d'Astroworld rejaillira sur Travis Scott, ou qu'il a le champ libre pour poursuivre sa success story ?

Truth is a deep kindness that teaches us to be content in our everyday life and share with the people the same happiness.

HU Staff: M. Cassidy @caldeoncass 
A woman on TikTok is encouraging other women to join her in a new challenge called the "Burn Bra Challenge," in ongoing calls to protest against Nike's decision to partner with transgender influencer Dylan Mulvaney. As previously revealed, the company announced its working relationship with Mulvaney earlier this month, wearing some of their activewear apparel including pants and a sports bra. The announcement was not received well over on social media, with people expressing their outrage and questioning why Nike couldn't just have hired a "real woman" to wear their workout gear. 
__________________________________________________
The problematic comments left the LGBTQ+ community startled, insisting that Nike had done a great thing by taking a chance on a transgender model, which showed that the company was clearly moving towards inclusivity. Well, according to the New York Post, the conversation is still being had almost a week later now that a woman is calling for a new trend to take off on TikTok where women are encouraged to burn their Nike sports bras to protest against the decision to have a transgender influencer promote women’s clothes. 
__________________________________________________
“Since the 1960s, we have been fighting for the right to be women. Nike, you should be ashamed of yourself,” a TikTok user by the name chatterbox.mama angrily said in her video. “You chose a little boy with no breasts and some junk in his pants to represent real women.” After saying she was done wearing Nike clothes, she burned her bras and encouraged other women to follow suit.

⬛️This is outrageous!⬛️ Extreme-Left Nike’s @nike distributor in Brazil, which has rights to sell the official national team jerseys for the FIFA World Cup @fifaworldcup , is no longer allowing customers to order personalized jerseys with “Jesus,” “Christ,” or other Christian terms following complaints from African paganists this week.

The FIFA World Cup begins on Sunday and is one of the planet’s most prestigious sporting events. It is particularly popular in Brazil, the winningest country in the history of the tournament with five championships.

Fisia, the company serving as Nike’s distributor in the country, reportedly added “Jesus” – a common male name in Latin America – and “Christ” to its list of prohibited personalization terms on Wednesday after the country’s Federal Public Ministry (MPF), its attorney general’s office, intervened out of concern for religious discrimination. Adherents to the Nigerian Lucumí Yoruba faith – known in the Spanish-speaking world as santería but commonly referred to in Brazil as Candomblé – complained to the government that the Nike website did not allow them to personalize World Cup jerseys with the names of their gods.

According to the BBC, prior to the online outrage from the African religious community in the country, names of deities (orixás) such as Xangô or Exu were not available for personalization, but “Jesus” and “Cristo” were. As one user on Twitter noted, on Tuesday, personalizing a shirt with the term “Amen, Jesus” was possible, but doing so with the Yoruba exaltation “Laroyê Exu” was not. The MPF then ordered an investigation into the matter that resulted in Nike and Fisia agreeing to add Christian terms to the list of prohibited terms for personalized jerseys.

Breitbart News attempted to order personalized Brazil national team jerseys on the Nike Brasil site on Friday. Attempting to use the names of African gods and “Jesus” and “Cristo” indeed resulted in a message reading, “personalization unavailable.”

Megan The Stallion Makes History As First Black Woman On Forbes 30 Under 30 Cover⁠
⁠
Blogged by: @Angiebonthebeat ⁠
⁠
#MeganTheStallion quickly became the female rapper to watch since bursting onto the scene doing cyphers on her college campus.⁠
⁠
Since then, the rapper has become famous for her infectious confidence and jaw-dropping lyrics and is now closing out 2022 on the heels of success. The H-Town Hottie now holds the title of the first black woman ever to grace the cover of Forbes’ 30 Under 30 issue.⁠
⁠
Headed by a combination of royalties, ticket sales, endorsements, and merchandise, the hot girl coach earned an estimated $13 million in 2022. Her endorsement resume includes the likes of Nike, Revlon, Cash App, Popeyes, and Flamin’ Hot Cheetos.⁠
⁠
That $13 million is comprised of around $2 million for her Cheetos Super Bowl ad, about $1 million for her Popeyes “Hottie Sauce,” $250,000 for her own Popeyes restaurant, and $3 million from Time Inc. for the upcoming documentary about her life. “I cannot fake it,” Megan told Forbes Senior Writer Jabari Young about her endorsement deals. “If I’m not naturally into it, I don’t want to sell it.”⁠
⁠
When discussing the trajectory of her career and how she’s the first black woman in this spot, she replied, “It’s really hard to be the first something in 2022, so ahh.”⁠
⁠
The rapper also opened up to the publication about her vulnerability in her music. Her latest album, “Traumazine” was her most personal project yet...to read the rest log on to BallerAlert.com (clickable link on profile)

Cops swarm Rihanna's house as man shows up to propose

Cops were called in to Rihanna's house yesterday, March 23, after a man showed up to ask for her hand in marriage.

Security officials told TMZ that the man traveled from South Carolina, walked up to Rihanna's home on Thursday where he faced her security.

After the man revealed he was there to propose to the singer, Rihanna's team called the cops right away. When officers arrived, they put the man in handcuffs, got him in a car and had a serious chat about his intentions.

It was further revealed that though the man who was dressed in a red Nike hoodie had not broken any laws, he was asked to leave and told not to return.

@nerdyalan has given us a new meaning to the term "clean kicks" by creating sneaker-inspired bathtubs using AI.⁠
⁠
The digital designs are influenced by an array of various sportswear brands’ most iconic colorways and models. There are versions that draw from the Swoosh including tubs that mimic the palettes of the Nike Air Foamposite Pro “Island Green” and the Air Max 95 “Neon” colorways. Jordan Brand is present in the assortment as there are also pieces that mirror the Air Jordan 11 “Concord,” Air Jordan 13 “Chicago” and the Air Jordan 15 “White/Black” iteration. Furthermore, there are tub renditions of the PUMA Suede and the adidas Superstar.⁠
⁠
Which is your favorite?⁠

In keeping with the holiday tradition of Kobe’s drops on Christmas Day, I am excited to share this Holiday Bundle. 

Kobe was a storyteller, and he had a passion for sharing life lessons through his multimedia company, Granity Studios. Included in this special Holiday Bundle is a complete set of his most creative stories. Some books from the set include the materials Kobe personally chose for his hardcover books. His attention to detail and the look and feel of these books was so important to him. The books will be available for purchase in these limited materials on our Granity website soon, while supplies last. 

And to further celebrate the holidays, I’ve added a pair of the Christmas Nike Kobe 6 Protro sneakers from my personal collection. 

My hope is that this Holiday Bundle reminds everyone that in everything he built, Kobe was committed to young people and wanted to inspire them on and off the court. He believed in the beauty of the process, in the strength that comes from inner magic, and in achieving the impossible. His legacy continues today. 

Proceeds benefit @mambamambacitasports 

Happy Holidays, Everyone. 

XO,
Vanessa Bryant

@hypebeastkicks: Official images of @travisscott's forthcoming Air Jordan 1 Low OG WMNS "Olive" colorway have finally surfaced. ⁠
⁠
La Flame adds olive hits to his signature reversed Swooshes and outsoles which spruce up the kicks with a military-esque look and feel. The insoles are treated with a variety of Cactus Jack and @jumpman23 graphics while pops of red show face on the tongue's Nike branding. Additionally, the kicks will come housed in a special cream and olive shoe box. ⁠
⁠
Expect these to launch in women's and kid's sizes come April 26, 2023. ⁠
Photo: Nike

@hypebeastkicks: Every year,  @nike celebrates Pride Month with a “Be True” collection that uses LGBTQIA+ themed color schemes. This year saw a slew of on-theme iterations of Dunk Lows, Cortez silhouettes, and more. Now, yet another Dunk Low in thematic hues has surfaced.⁠
⁠
Unlike 2022’s release, this SB Dunk Low “Be True” begins with a textured mesh base in white. Leather overlays in yellow and lavender then arrive with a reddish Swoosh to complete the upper. Pride-themed detailing appears on the tongue and continues with a sun and rainbow characters on the heel area to round out the look.⁠
⁠
While there has been no release date announced for the pair, fans can remain hopeful for an eventual release via Nike and select retailers come next Pride Month. For now, swipe for a closer look at the kicks.⁠
Photo: @yankeekicks⁠
