Erling Haaland loves a fashion crime 🚔

👕 In the last few months Haaland has been spotted in both Adidas and Puma clothing, sometimes both at the same time. 

❌ “Normally it’s not allowed to wear Adidas and Nike together, so that is a little bit why I did it,” explained Haaland in an interview. 

🧠 But this probably wasn’t just for fun. Haaland doesn’t have a boot deal, and as one of the most promising footballers, he has been courted by Adidas, Nike, and Puma. His constantly changing (and sometimes clashing) wardrobe was probably a tactic. He wanted to show the brands that his final decision could go any way, they had to fight for his signature. 

🥇And it looks like Haaland has made his choice. A few days ago, he posted photos wearing a new Nike collection, the exclusive collaboration with Tiffany&co. You can’t buy the jacket he was wearing on the open market, Nike only gives it to special people (as of now.) 

✍🏻 It therefore looks as if Haaland has gone with Nike, a decision that was already reported in the press but unconfirmed. 

🤯 To understand why Haaland chose Nike, and how his decision could unbalance the sportswear market for years to come, check out our YouTube video (link in bio)

Description:
Nike’s Banned “Maxsight” UV-blocking contact lenses (2006)

Bausch & Lomb and Nike developed the soft lenses, which are indicated for daily wear. They designed the lenses to protect athletes eyes from ultraviolet light. The lenses also enhance contrast in light conditions, helping athletes see fast-moving objects, such as baseballs, more clearly despite speed of travel. They were banned because they offered athletes an unfair advantage. 👁 🔴

Description:
The Blueberry Blue Nike Dunk is a refreshing and vibrant sneaker that exudes a cool, summery aesthetic. This particular iteration of the Nike Dunk embraces a striking blueberry blue colorway, which instantly catches the eye and adds a unique touch to any outfit.

The upper of the shoe is crafted from a combination of premium leather and suede materials, ensuring durability and a luxurious feel. The blueberry blue hue covers the majority of the upper, creating a bold and cohesive look. Subtle branding details, such as the iconic Nike Swoosh, are delicately embroidered on the sides, adding a touch of classic style.

The design of the Blueberry Blue Nike Dunk showcases a clean and timeless silhouette, characterized by a low-top profile and a padded collar for comfort. The contrasting white midsole provides a crisp and clean aesthetic, while also offering excellent cushioning and support.

In terms of design accents, the Blueberry Blue Nike Dunk keeps it minimalistic and sleek. The color scheme takes center stage, with the vibrant blue shade dominating the shoe's overall appearance. This simplicity allows the bold color to make a statement, making it an ideal choice for those who want to add a pop of color to their sneaker collection.

Whether you're strolling the city streets or hitting the skate park, the Blueberry Blue Nike Dunk offers both style and functionality. Its eye-catching colorway and versatile design make it a standout choice for those who appreciate the intersection of fashion and sportswear.

Overall, the Blueberry Blue Nike Dunk is a visually captivating sneaker that embodies a fresh and vibrant vibe. Its distinctive blue hue and clean design make it a must-have for sneaker enthusiasts looking to make a bold fashion statement.

Here’s a look at the upcoming Nike Fly Milk Blazer Premium. It is a tribute on Nike SB’s behalf to Jeff and the Fly Skateshop he started in Shanghai after quiting his previous job working at a milk processing plant. The theme of the Blazer involves a missing person ad on a carton utilizing the same color scheme as a milk carton in China (the Chinese characters on the heel translate to milk). Due to the countless amount of time spent by Jeff, this can be related to being “missing” hence the use of his picture on the

⁠

”You are an essential component to the success of your community! We welcome comments that contribute to a positive and constructive discussion."⁠

Venezia FC was relegated last season from Serie A, the top league of Italian football, and is languishing in Serie B. But the small football club with a Unesco World Heritage home city is winning in other ways.

Named “football's most fashionable club” by one fashion publication, Venezia's €110 ($129) football kits are almost like an affordable luxury item. The club has opened two retail locations in the last 12 months in addition to the flagship store just off Venice’s famous Rialto Bridge, which bustles with tourists seeking trendy souvenirs to take home—whether or not they’re football fans. Sales of merchandise went from €730,000 in 2019-20 (the last year with Nike) to surpass €3 million in 2021-22. The club expects even better figures this year.

Football kits have increasingly become fashion staples. While most uniforms get launched with a photo of a star player out on the pitch, Venezia took a different approach to reinvent itself and get noticed on the world stage, leaning on Italy's reputation for high fashion. And largely, it's worked. Tap the link in bio for more, via @bloombergpursuits.

@louisvuitton is partnering with @doverstreetmarketginza to exhibit and sell select pieces from Virgil Abloh's tenure at the French maison.⁠
⁠
From October 29 to November 15, shoppers can head to DSM's Tokyo location to get an up-close look at eight ensembles spanning Abloh's time at Louis Vuitton, a nearly four-year-long run cut short by the designer's unexpected death in November 2021. A selection of custom and archival designs will also be on view.⁠
⁠
It's unclear which specific runway looks and standalone garments will make an appearance. The sheer prospect of whittling Abloh's portfolio down to just eight ensembles is a daunting task — there are nearly too many iconic moments from his reign as Louis Vuitton's artistic director of menswear.⁠
⁠
To name just a handful: the harnesses and holographic bags from Abloh's inaugural Louis Vuitton collection (SS19); the light-up Keepall (FW19); Louis Vuitton x NIGO LV² (Pre-Fall 2020); the sweater covered in stuffed puppets (SS21); Louis Vuitton x Nike's ultra-luxe Air Force 1s.⁠
⁠
There's no question that the pieces that do make the cut will end up selling for sky-high prices — back in February, pairs of the Abloh-designed AF1s, one of the late designer's last projects, auctioned at Sotheby's for over $100,000.⁠
⁠
But don't let that deter you from stopping by the exhibition and sale. You can also pick up a copy of Assouline's Louis Vuitton: Virgil Abloh book, a retrospective of his work at the house, at the event for a comparatively small sum of $150.⁠
⁠
✍️: @paulybyalexforalexandrapauly⁠
📷️: Getty

@hypebeastkicks:⁠ When @tomsachs and @nike first unveiled their General Purpose Shoe, they took a subtle dig at the sneaker industry. The shoe was introduced as “boring,” going on to add that “your sneakers shouldn’t be the most exciting thing about you.” What followed was a mission statement for the latest NikeCraft evolution, that honed in on simplicity and footwear being used as a functional tool, so that you can “focus on getting a little bit faster, a little bit sharper, on finding the signal in the noise.”⁠
⁠
Hypebeast got the opportunity to sit with the artist to discuss the evolution of NikeCraft, and how his new release builds on the Mars Yard. Hit the link in bio for the full feature.⁠

Description:
#Nike moves to crack down on bots and resellers with penalties: the company will add restocking fees, refuse refunds and suspend accounts of resellers

The sneaker company added new terms for U.S. online sales this month to prevent resellers from purchasing its products and reselling them on the secondary market using automated technology or software. The Wall Street Journal first reported the changes Tuesday.

The news comes as Nike realized how resellers have benefitted from the market. Just five days after the Louis Vuitton x Nike Air Force 1 collaboration back in July, the shoes, which were sold at a fixed price of $2,527 USD, appeared on the resale market and sold for approximately $9,785 USD on another platform, KREAM.

Industry insiders believe that Nike is setting the precedent for future resalers and that its revision of its terms and conditions may spearhead the way sneakers are traded. 

The new policy allows Nike to cancel any orders for purchases if they suspect that the person is buying for the sake of reselling. 

Nike Korea’s latest move puts the industry on high alert and begs to question if Nike as a whole or other brands will move in the same direction.

Whew! The parent company of the alcoholic beverage Bud Light Beer has seen a huge loss in value following news of its partnership with transgender influencer Dylan Mulvaney. The 26-year-old, who infuriated women earlier this month when it was announced she had also signed a deal with Nike to promote workout apparel such as sports bras, is now being blamed for the $5 billion slump Anheuser-Busch has seen this week.
________________________________________________
Per the Dow Jones Market Data Group, the company was down 4.7 percent, decreasing its value from $132 billion to $127 billion in market cap. Shortly after the news that Mulvaney had partnered with the brewing firm, which is headquartered in St. Louis, Missouri, the maker’s stock already dropped more than 1.5 percent hours after the campaign went public. Social media users have since taken to multiple different platforms, sharing their anger and frustration about the deal with Mulvaney, saying they were going to boycott drinking Bud Light beer.
___________________________________________________ 
Rock star Kid Rock was perhaps one of the most famous names who expressed his disapproval of the partnership after he posted a video of himself shooting at Bud Light cases for target practice. “Let me say something to all of you and be as clear and concise as possible,” before shooting at the cases and saying, “F*** Bud Light, and f*** Anheuser-Busch.” Country singer Travis Tritt said that Anheusr-Busch drinks would no longer be served at any of his concerts.

The last of this compendium on the sneaker choices made by the 🐐 during December 2002. 
-
Hopefully, you’ll agree that these were the best of those choices - the ‘Cool Grey’ Air Jordan XI 🔥
-
Whilst these were released to the public in March 2001, Mike laced these up a total of six times in this month (tied for most with new and not out yet XVIII) so must have been pretty taken with them 👀
-
They were on MJ’s feet for the following matchups:
• 10th December 2002 vs Trailblazers
• 17th December 2002 at Hawks
• 18th December 2002 vs Grizzlies
• 28th December 2002 vs Hawks
• 30th December 2002 at Magic
• 31st December 2002 vs Spurs
-
It wouldn’t be the last time that we would see these on foot during Mike’s final season in the NBA. Most noticeably he wore them for his true last game at Madison Square Garden as he gave it to the Knicks one last time.

Argentina celebrated their World Cup triumph in special versions of their home shirt now complete with three stars!

The shirt now also features the World Champion shield in the centre.

But rereleasing a shirt to update the stars isn't something new.

In 1994 it wasn't just the stars on the actual crest that needed updating.

The design of their shirt was literally the crest. So after the win in USA in 1994, the crest within the shirt design itself got an update.

After France won the World Cup in 1998, they added a star to their iconic shirt celebrating their first triumph.

Once again with Brazil win 2002, they rereleased their Nike shirt complete with 5 stars.

They're going to run out of room soon.

Well this is definitely not good. As expected, NBA star Ja Morant is currently facing consequences for flashing a gun on social media… for the second time. 
__________________________________________________
As previously reported, the Memphis Grizzlies have suspended him from all team activities after an IG Live showed the star guard holding a gun while rapping to a song with a friend. The Grizzlies announced the suspension over the weekend and said the league is pending a review of the incident. "We are aware of the social media post involving Ja Morant and are in the process of gathering more information," NBA spokesperson Mike Bass previously said.
__________________________________________________
Morant who, was suspended by the NBA in March over a similar incident did release a statement to apologize for his latest actions. He said, “I know I’ve disappointed a lot of people who have supported me,” Morant said in a statement via ESPN. “This is a journey and I recognize there is more work to do. My words may not mean much right now, but I take full accountability for my actions. I’m committed to continuing to work on myself.” Despite that, it looks like he’s about to have a tough wake-up call. While many are speculating his future with the NBA, sports fans have noticed that Morant’s Hunger Ja 1 sneakers are no longer listed on the Nike or Finish Line apps. The Hunger Ja 1s were expected to release on May 25, TMZ notes.

Great night at Camp Nou between @fcbarcelona and @mancity. High quality game apart from some very dubious keeping and Haaland is an absolute beast in the flesh. Sad to see Mbette horribly injured at the end. 

Mixed feelings because ultimately it was for an excellent cause, raising money for ALS research by the @fundacion.luzon #teamals #equipals. 

But this club has mortgaged its future, selling naming rights to the likes of Spotify and is being run into financial ruin for the hope of short term success. Hopefully the situation can be rectified but in the era of instant gratification and immediate results the outlook is bleak. @theathletic_uk covered this in amazing and frankly terrifying detail. Pause for thought that things are so bad they were forced to allow the 🐐 Leo Messi to leave because they couldn’t afford to pay him. 

All in all a great experience but even the great Barcelona are no longer mes que in club.

@hypebeastkicks: Despite the evergrowing footwear industry, the growth of global fashion sneaker sales actually fell in 2022. According to reports, the high growth phase which resulted in a 19.5% spike in 2021 looks to have ended as global sneaker sales in 2022 totaled $152.4 billion USD. The decline continues to show that the market is changing, with the sneaker industry now projected to grow at an annual average rate of 3.6% until 2027. ⁠
⁠
While big brands like @nike and @adidas will likely continue to be on the rise in the long run, the major brands are currently facing oversupply inventory issues and declining sales in China. To read the full report, head to the link in bio.⁠

I'm writing this a bit teary eyed. I've worked so hard to bring you this book and I'm so excited to finally announce it here.

Exactly 8 years ago this week, I came out on Facebook. Terrified, I sat before my computer. "This post is to affirm your suspicions: I am transgender," I wrote.Everything went very quickly from then: Hundreds of interviews and speeches, appearing on the Ellen Show, 60 Minutes, and the Olympic Channel, consulting with industry leaders like the NCAA and Nike, providing support groups and mentorship to thousands of trans and queer people, and so much more.The need for this type of work - for trans inclusion and gender literacy - has only exponentially increased as time elapses. And it is most urgent now. This is why I've written this book.He/She/They is a culmination of everything I have ever worked on into a book. It is the culmination of my years of speaking, training, mentoring, consulting, clinical research, and facilitating support groups into a resource for you that is driven by narrative and humanity, and backed by research and science.Filled with nuggets of my own humanity - and some stories I've never shared publicly before - I've been working on He/She/They since I was born, really. It is deeply personal and I can't wait for you to read this fall.Pre-order He/She/They anywhere you buy books, or at hstbook.com.Allies, this is a chance to step into the work - heart first. He/She/They will ask you to examine yourself, too, because this is where allyship truly begins.And to all my trans siblings out there: this book is also for you. For those of us finding our voices, for those of us who don’t know how to stand up for ourselves yet, and for any of us who are still learning the words to best understand ourselves. This is also for you.I hope you love it.Sincerely,SBP.S. A huge thanks to my team at @hachettego - Renee Sedliar, my editor, especially, who has worked so patiently and carefully with me to ensure my voice is as strong as it can be, as well as Michael Barrs, Sharon Kunz, and Ashley Kiedrowski; and my agent, Susan Canavan who has always had my back.

Description:
For a writer-director-actor who’s had every chance to sit on top of the world, few have cultivated an aura of pathos like Ben Affleck. Yet somehow, in spite of his woebegone spirit or because of it, he has become one of the most reliably valuable directors we’ve got, as well as an actor whose performances consistently range from good to low-key great.

#Air, Ben Affleck’s fifth movie as a director — and now streaming on Amazon Prime — may sound like a bore if you don’t care about business, basketball, or athletic shoes. But Affleck uses classic stealth means to make you care. 

It’s 1984 and Matt Damon stars as Sonny Vaccaro, a middle-aged businessguy in need of a hit, finds himself against a wall: he’s having trouble finding a young, up-and-coming basketball player to represent Nike products. Many of the names he and his colleagues float have been all but forgotten today, but one keeps coming up: the company would love to have a rookie named Michael Jordan wear their shoes, but he’s already promised his allegiance to another company, Adidas.

We already know Affleck is a good director. But we’ve also seen him at his lowest, contemplating his worth as a man and finding it wanting. Then he comes out and makes a casually superb little movie, almost as if it were no big deal to do so.

At the link in bio, find out why we don’t deserve Ben Affleck. 

Photograph by Ana Carballosa—Prime

Description:
HU Staff: Maurice C. @caldeoncass
If transgender influencer Dylan Mulvaney hasn't found herself in enough controversy this past month, she is now going viral yet again over a resurfaced video where she said it should be illegal to use the wrong pronouns on people. In the TikTok video, originally posted back in October 2022, the 26-year-old sounded off on her thoughts about journalists who had been referring to her using he/him pronouns, which Mulvaney was clearly offended about. She titled the TikTok video with the words "Adult Bullies" while addressing the hate that has come her way after gaining a lot of popularity online. 
__________________________________________________
Mulvaney, who recently partnered up with Nike for an endorsement deal, called out the unidentified journalists who she was upset over because they had called her a "man" even though she identifies as a female. “Like, the articles written about me using ‘he’ pronouns and calling me a man over and over again, I feel like that should be illegal. I don’t know, that’s just bad journalism,” she said. Furthermore, Mulvaney said being misgendered in articles about her was worse than the derogatory terms people have used against her, such as those who have called her a "pedophile."
__________________________________________________
“I’m reminding myself that those people actually feel like they’re doing the Lord’s work,” she went on to express in a passionate tone. “They believe that their bullying actually is the right thing to do, and I’m the one to blame when I’m just over here trying to live my best life.” As we previously reported, Mulvaney caused outrage from Bud Light fans after the firm partnered with her for their latest campaign, which caused its parent company, Anheuser-Busch, value to drop by $5 billion within days after the announcement.

The 2022/23 @laliga champions have unveiled their new Nike home kit for the upcoming season and it's the first to be inspired by the club's women's team. The new @fcbarcelona jersey includes a unique Barça badge with a symbolic diamond set into the crest. This significant design detail celebrates the genesis of FC Barcelona women's football, which dates back to Christmas Day 1970 when a group of pioneering women became the first to play a match at the Camp Nou. This game proved the spark for the first FC Barcelona women’s supporters club to be formed a year later in 1971, which used the club badge combined with a diamond for their logo. That game has become, over time, the symbol of a struggle of perseverance to achieve the recognition that @fcbfemeni has today. The new shirt also arrives with classic broad stripes in original blaugrana colours.

Chitose Abe's @sacaiofficial issues collaborations so often that they often spill out beyond seasonal collections and into occasional pop-ups or standalone events. There are plenty of special things created for Sacai's proper offerings but there's often just way too much for a single Sacai collection.⁠
⁠
Though they weren't the main event at Sacai's January 22 FW23 presentation at Paris Fashion Week, Sacai's latest @nike collaboration was visible in several colorful permutations underfoot, bringing together the asymmetric lacing.⁠
⁠
Alongside the new Nike sneakers, Sacai FW23 also introduces a collaboration with @carharttwip, further ingratiating the workwear stalwart with luxury labels.⁠
⁠
Sacai's take on Carhartt workwear is typical of previous Sacai joint efforts, epitomizing Sacai's signature approach to garment hybridization. Here, Carhartt chore coats are reimagined as knit jackets, longline faux fur-trimmed parkas, or multifaceted layering pieces with bomber-style pockets and plackets, complete with co-branded Carhartt x Sacai tag.⁠
⁠
There are even chunky Carhartt-branded sweaters, taking the blue collar Detroit brand to stylish new heights.⁠
⁠
📷️: @sacaiofficial

Description:
The latest edition of the Lobster Series, we elevate and bridge the gap between art, fashion, luxury, and unconventional creativity taking visual queues from the surrealist painter, Salvador Dali. Our exclusive special packaging is complete with a custom box featuring Dali’s famous ‘Lobster Telephone,’ circa 1938. A classic example of surrealism, Dali believed that combining two unrelated objects could reveal the secret desires of the unconscious.⁠
 ⁠
In the same overarching theme, Concepts and MEDICOM TOY collaborate for the first time with an orange all-over lobster speckle BE@RBRICK set arriving in 100% and 400% figures. Concepts and MEDICOM TOY, both founded in 1996, have taken the approach aimed to create collectible pieces of art rather than conventional toys. Thus, in the theme of surrealism and combining the most unrelated objects, bear-shaped figures and the lobster splatter, we announce that this limited edition anniversary BE@RBRICK set is only available with our exclusive packaging. ⁠
 ⁠
As a nod to celebrating anniversaries and long-standing partnerships, each shoe will come with custom bands, silver symbolizing Concepts' 25th anniversary, and an emerald color symbolizing the 20th anniversary of Nike SB.⁠

Download and turn on notifications for the SNKRS app and the CNCPTS app for more details.

When Ben Affleck asked Michael Jordan who he wanted to play his mom in ‘Air,’ Jordan knew immediately: @violadavis. The only problems were that Davis is one of the most sought-after actors in Hollywood and the script originally only had one line for the character.

Directed by Affleck, ‘Air’ tells the story of the endorsement deal between Nike and Jordan, a rookie at the time, that led to the creation of the Air Jordan shoe line.

While speaking to the audience at the film’s premiere at SXSW, Affleck said he asked Jordan if he had any wishes for the film. Among them was the portrayal of his mother, according to Variety.

‘It was the first time I saw this look cross his face,’ Affleck said. ’It was a look of reverence, of awe, of love, and gratitude, and innocence. He said, ‘None of this would have ever happened without my mother.’ I said, ‘Who would you like to play your mom?’ He said, ‘Well, it has to be Viola Davis.’’

Affleck told the Hollywood Reporter that at the time Jordan made the request, the role was very small.

‘Oh my God, he wants me to offer this to Viola Davis,’ he told the publication. ‘How am I going to offer Viola Davis a movie with one line? That’s not going to happen.’

Affleck said that he begged Davis to play the role. Along with Matt Damon and his wife Jennifer Lopez, they expanded the role and were able to get Davis to sign on.

‘This is a hard business,’ he said at SXSW. ‘It’s hard to know if you’re successful. It’s hard to know if you’ve accomplished something. But honest to God, I always felt that if I was a director one day, and I had Viola Davis in a movie, that would really be something. That would mean the world to me. And it does.’

The film stars Davis, Affleck, Damon, Jason Bateman, Chris Messina, and Damian Delano Young, who plays Jordan. It premieres in theaters on April 5.

⚡ One of the main reasons to add the Nike SB Dunk Supreme to your collection is its rarity and exclusivity. Supreme collaborations are known for their limited production runs, making them highly sought after by collectors. Owning a pair of Nike SB Dunk Supreme signifies not only your appreciation for high-quality footwear but also your connection to the world of street culture and fashion.

With the release of the highly-anticipated @supermariomovie just over a month away, sneaker designer @andu.c has just revealed his latest custom, a @nike Dunk Low “What the Super Mario.”⁠
⁠
The conceptual pair arrives completely mismatched, featuring a colorful patchwork assembly of Chiou's favorite characters and items from the Mario universe. Mystery Box graphics cover the toe box, character-related references decorate the heel counter, sawtoothed Bullet Bills are featured on the mudguard, and Toad’s polka-dotted mushroom hat is represented on the medial panels. Other subtle nods include Yoshi, Boomerang Flower, Wario, Princess Peach, Bowser, Donkey Kong, Princess Daisy, and Stone Block.⁠
Photo: Andrew Chiou

Description:
Nike SB Dunk Low ‘Sandy’ / eBay

Back in 2003, Nike SB took to eBay to auction off a special pair of Dunk Lows colored to resemble the marketplace’s signature logo. All proceeds from the listing — which ended at a final bid of $30,000 — were put to the construction of new skate parks throughout the Portland area. Though only a single pair of said shoes were sold, there are reportedly three in existence, one of which was sawed into four separate parts.

To honor the life of the late Sandy Bodecker, who’s responsible for building up Nike SB to what is today, Nike is literally putting the pieces of the above-mentioned Dunk Low back together. But rather than connect said segments seamlessly, the team have opted to fill in the spaces with a see-through TPU. The rest of the construction is faithful to the original colorway, however, representing eBay’s signature red, blue, yellow, and green palette. In addition, an image of Bodecker himself is printed onto the sockliner of the left foot; the right opts for an on-foot image of the original, ripped apart eBay Dunk.

🗞️ #SAFC today announced a new multi-year partnership with Nike, the world's leading footwear and apparel company.

In collaboration with the Just Sport Group, the famous Nike Swoosh will continue to adorn the Club's playing kit and training wear until the summer of 2027.

Nike have supplied SAFC with teamwear since 2020 and the Club's bespoke 2021-22 and 2022-23 home shirts led to record sales, with the former cementing its spot as a fan favourite following the Lads’ 2022 Play-Off Final victory at Wembley Stadium.

The new agreement will also see North East-based Just Sport Group lead the Club's online and stadium-based retail operation, which will include the launch of a brand-new online store.

To facilitate the changeover process, supporters are advised that the existing online store and Stadium of Light store will be closed from 17:00 on Tuesday 27 June until 10:00 on Thursday 06 July.

Fans are thanked for their patience and understanding throughout this period and we look forward to unveiling the Club's new 2023-24 home and away kits upon reopening.

SAFC’s Chief Operating Officer, Steve Davison, said: "We have enjoyed a successful partnership with the Just Sport Group and Nike over the past three years, so we are delighted to be strengthening our relationship with a world-renowned brand that is also embedded within the North East. Following regular dialogue with our supporters' groups and the wider fan base, we recognised the importance of improving our retail experience this summer and we look forward to supporting the Just Sport Group in delivering an enhanced service throughout the next four years."

Grammy 2023 🏆

No último domingo 5 de fevereiro, ocorreu a 65.ª cerimônia do Grammy Awards, onde tivemos a presença de praticamente toda a indústria da musica global, o evento que sempre chama atenção pelos looks extremamente especiais dos artistas, sendo eles em sua grande maioria feitos exclusivamente para o evento e sob medida para cada artista, por isso acabam sendo considerados inestimáveis como é o caso do look do Pharrell Willians e de sua esposa Helen Lasichanh.

Não podemos deixar de mencionar um dos Rappers mais aclamados dessa geração Kendrick Lamar, levou pela terceira vez o Grammy de melhor álbum de Rap com o "Mr. Morale & the Big Steppers", além disso Kendrick também levou mais dois prêmios o de Melhor Performance e o de Melhor Música, totalizando assim 17 gramofones sendo o terceiro rapper com mais títulos da história.

There was a bunch of celebrities who popped out in Los Angeles to help Cardi B celebrate her big 30th birthday last night. 
________________________________________________
Stars like Chloe Bailey, Halle Bailey, Karruche Tran, Coco Jones, Tiffany Haddish, and more attended her big celebration. Jamie Foxx even pulled up to the hot scene but shockingly had trouble getting in, according to @tmz_tv. 
___________________________________________________ 
In a video taken by Backgrid, the legendary actor can be seen switching out his Nike Air Force 1s sneakers for a fresh pair before walking to the venue. As he approached the door with his entourage and security, the actor was held up by a doorman who wouldn’t let him in! After a few minutes, Jamie made his way back to his Rolls Royce where paparazzi asked why he was rejected. That’s when a door guy came running after the star to let him know that he’s actually cool to go in... but Foxx wasn't having it, saying, "No, we not good. Nah ni**a, it's all good! I love you, but it was too much." Sources say Cardi had no idea what was going on in the front as she was enjoying her birthday bash inside. It was also said that Jamie was ultimately turned away because there were too many guests with him.

Nike Has Officially Cut Ties With Kyrie Irving

Kyrie Irving is no longer a Nike athlete ... a spokesperson for the company announced Monday.

Irving, whose future with the retail giant was in question after they suspended him for tweeting about a controversial, antisemitic film ... has cut ties with the NBA star, according to NBA insider Shams Charania.

As we previously reported, Nike put its relationship with Ky on ice on November 4 ... suspending Irving. Despite satisfying the team and league with his apology, as well as other steps, the Swoosh indicated their relationship with Irving was probably done after the suspension.

In an interview with CNBC, Phil Knight, co-founder and chairman of the manufacturing conglomerate, said Irving's relationship with the company was "likely over."

"Kyrie stepped over the line. It's kind of that simple," Knight said. "He made some statements that we just can't abide by, and that's why we ended the relationship. I was fine with that."

Kyrie joined the Nike family in 2014 ... releasing his signature Kyrie 1 basketball shoe as a member of the Cavs in his third NBA season (Source: TMZ)

Nike has filed a lawsuit against Lululemon, alleging they have infringed on patented footwear designs.⁠
⁠
The accusation from Nike is that it has suffered economic harm and irreparable injury due to Lululemon’s sale of the Chargefeel Mid, Chargefeel Low, Blissfeel, and Strongfeel shoes which they say use patented designs that enhance performance from their Flyknit running shoe.⁠
⁠
Nike said its three patent claims are about textile elements, including knitted features, webbed areas, and tubular structures on the footwear. One patent claim also addresses footwear’s performance.⁠
⁠
“Nike’s claims are unjustified, and we look forward to proving our case in court,” a Lululemon spokesperson said in a statement Tuesday.⁠
⁠
At this time, Nike is seeking unspecified damages.⁠
⁠
The case is Nike Inc v. Lululemon Inc. USA⁠.⁠
⁠

@market comes through to troll @nike in a way only Market knows how. ⁠
⁠
"Just Sue It" and "Call my Lawyer" are some of the Bape-inspired tees market just dropped. The brand even attempts to spill some tea,  stating that "In 1972 Nike stole the design for the 'Cortez' from Onitsuka Tiger in Japan," a strong claim from Market. ⁠
⁠
For those in the know, this could ring true as the Onitsuka Tiger is deeply rooted in Nike's origins. Blue Ribbon Sports was Nike before Nike and Phil Knight went to Onitsuka to bring the Tigers to the western market. After bringing the Tiger to the US Phil would work with Onitsuka to prototype different iterations of the sneaker. Years later, in 1967, the Cortez was born with notable features from the Tiger.⁠
⁠
Market's cease-and-desist-worthy tees are available now for US$45.

Description:
Pick one from this @nike X @travisscott ‘Earth Pack’ concept? Did Nike miss a trick on this model? Personally I think they did🤔
.
The shoe itself is significantly different from the AM1 sure it uses the same shape but mid panel, heel panel, tongue, lacing, lining are all different. It’s only the front mudguard and midsole which are pulled from the AM1. Even if they wanted to use these features of the AM1, they should have called it something different to distinguish it or even tried an entirely different midsole wouldn’t have bothered me. I was mostly impressed and pleasantly surprised with the materials and build quality from Nike on these too 🤌🏻
.
It’s interesting too you have labels like NB taking the success of the 550 ALD and then using that to pump out every colour way possible on a basic white shoe which in my mind is cashing in. Fair enough but not something I can get on with. Same principle with the Jordan 1 tbh, so every brand does it. 
.
I am not talking about that here wanting 100s more releases. Like with this pack let’s have some creative colourway themes, I personally like that in a release. Sadly it seems when a label gets success with a model these days we get 100s of lazy pairs just pumped out, without much thought, other than let’s slap another colour on it, oh we haven’t done purple yet 😂. Is that human nature to cash in? Why can’t they do a dozen pairs then put it to bed even revisit it again in a few years. Just have to look at the 997/998 currently on hiatus but everything goes in cycles with sneakers that’s the way of most things and is what makes things desirable and respectable👍🏻
.
So long story short, I think they could have produced at least a few packs of these I would have been down for that without doubt as this is definitely a sneaker I would have liked to see more of. Stay tuned for a few more packs I have come up with😏

Nike have confirmed that they will stop using kangaroo leather in the construction of their football boots – including the next generation of the Tiempo franchise – and all products in 2023. The new Tiempo Legend Elite, expected to launch this summer, will debut with a new Nike-only, proprietary synthetic upper. The news follows PUMA’s recent launch of the latest KING model which features a 'K-Better' upper – a completely new, non-animal based material that also marks an end to PUMA's use of kangaroo leather. Nike's announcement also comes after the introduction of a bill in mid-January in Oregon – where Nike is headquartered – that would ban the sale of "any part of a dead kangaroo or any product containing a part of a dead kangaroo."

@tiffanyandco has officially unveiled its upcoming collaborative @nike Air Force 1 Low.⁠
⁠
The sneaker has been done up in subtle fashion boasting a premium suede upper in black paired with a contrasting Swoosh in the signature Tiffany blue. Other details include rope lacing, "Tiffany" branding on the tongue, and a metal embellishment on the heel.⁠
⁠
To accompany the sneaker, Tiffany & Co. also looks to deliver a number of accessories to complement the release including a whistle, brush, lace dubrae, and shoehorn all boasting the jewelry company's debossed insignia. The Tiffany & Co. x Nike Air Force 1 will be released globally via SNKRS app on March 7 in US men's sizing 3.5-18 and will retail for $400 USD.⁠

An orange and red woven tongue label serve as a nod to an early UNDEFEATED release, while an all over print footbed provides a hidden detail. A subtle debossed 5-strike at the heel and easy to remove “UNDFTD” branded dubrae, unique to this silhouette, finish the shoe.

Eastbay, the Company Behind the Iconic ’90s Sneaker Catalog, To Close Its Doors For Good⁠
⁠
Blogged by: @thefineauthor⁠
⁠
Remember the days of passing around those #Eastbay catalogs in school, fantasizing with your friends over the latest sneaker? Sadly, the world of technology has led us further away from those much simpler times, and the iconic retailer has come to grips with this realization.⁠
⁠
On Tuesday, #WisconsinPublicRadio dropped the bombshell that the famed sports company would close down for good in 2023. Over 200 employees will be laid off when Eastbay shuts the doors of its Wausau, Wisconsin headquarters. This is the same town where the company was founded in 1980 and was still a local icon, despite its fall from grace.⁠
⁠
Eastbay launched its own clothing line in 1990 that consisted of jerseys, jackets, and other sports paraphernalia. Most notable in operation was the massive collection of sneakers offered in its monthly magazines. #Nike, #Adidas, #Reebok, #Converse, and other brands helped drive the company’s popularity, and in 1997, Eastbay was acquired by #FootLockerInc. #BSNSPORTS purchased it from Foot Locker this year.⁠
⁠
While the popular sneaker books were loved through the early 2000s, online shopping replaced the need for manual ordering and mailing in check payments. The Wausau’s Chamber of Commerce saw the closure from a mile away, pointing to a less busy parking lot at Eastbay headquarters and decreased operations.⁠
⁠
“You drive around and look at what’s going on, and you see diminished numbers… and those are warnings,” stated #DaveEckmann, President, and CEO of the Wausau Chamber of Commerce…to read the rest log on to BallerAlert.com (clickable link on profile).⁠

Nike and @corinthians have unveiled the club's 2023 fourth jersey and winner of the #MantoDoCorinthians kit design campaign. The eight month campaign, which saw over 2,000 fan-designed jerseys submitted, allowed Corinthians fans to vote from eight final designs. The winning jersey – named the "Origens" jersey – was designed by Leonardo Fojo, who won the final round of voting with 56% of the votes. The jersey was unveiled as a giant flag over the stands with the slogan "CREATED BY THE FIEL. CHOSEN BY THE PEOPLE" at the Neo Química Arena before kick-off against Fluminense. The design of the jersey pays tribute to the club's first uniform and the Campo do Lenheiro - Corinthians' first football field. The beige shirt features dust details representing the hardworking fans, with the Corinthians Paulista shield and Nike logo included in the center. The inscription "É o equipe do povo" (It's the people's team) emphasizes the club's working-class identity.

4 Linebacker Drills to Help with Tackling 🦍

1st Drill: Feet shoulder-width apart rolling out of your Hips focusing on a 6 inch pop W/ Proper angles in the knees and ankles.

2nd drill : Long stride , short stride preparing to step to contact Chest out with arms ready to wrap about the ball carrier.

3rd Drill : bag behind the feet eliminating any false step! Gain ground immediately down hill then coming to balance ! Step to contact hitting on the rise ! Feet continue to run through the ball carrier.

Agarwal’s tryst with entrepreneurship began in 1983 when he founded the “Action" sports shoe brand. In 2005, he launched “Campus” sports shoes for prices under $10. The budget pricing helped Campus make big enough strides to compete with global brands such as Nike, Adidas and Puma, which sell sports shoes for upwards of $35.

“He capitalized on the huge vacuum in the Indian sports shoe market—in the $10 to $40 price range,” says Campus’ chief financial officer Raman Chawla.

An April 2022 report by Gurgaon consulting firm Technopak notes that in fiscal 2021, Campus was India’s largest player in the branded sports and athleisure (fusion of “athletic” and “leisure”) segment, both in value and number of shoes. It has a 17% market share by value and nearly 25% by volume.

Campus sold 13 million pairs in 2021, notching up $94 million in revenue. This was a slight dip from the previous year’s revenue of $95 million, due to the pandemic, but sales are marching upward again: Campus recorded revenue of $111 million for the nine months ended December 2021.

Going public notwithstanding, Campus remains a family affair. Agarwal’s son Nikhil Aggarwal, 37, an industrial engineer from Purdue University, started working at Campus in 2008 and became CEO nine years later. Nikhil’s wife, Prerna, is the chief marketing officer. The founder’s wife, Vinod Agarwal, who used to lead supply chain initiatives and a network of fabricators for Campus’ sports shoes, was on the board until September 2021.

The rocky relationship between @nike and @kyrieirving has now officially come to a close. As reported by @shamsnba, Irving is no longer a Nike athlete following the suspension of the brand’s partnership with the Brooklyn Nets guard last month.⁠
⁠
In November, Nike joined the Nets in taking action following Irving’s sharing of a film that expressed antisemitic views. Before this, Irving’s future with Nike was called into question due to his response to COVID-19 that led to him missing a significant portion of the 2021-2022 NBA season. In addition, Irving has previously shared his dissatisfaction with the brand, posting in 2021 that the upcoming Kyrie Infinity is “trash” and that Nike planned to release them without his consent.⁠
⁠
What’s next for Irving is up in the air as the Nets star continues to boast averages that include over 24 points per game. As for Nike, its classic partnerships with superstars such as LeBron James are supported by a growing roster of talent for both the Swoosh and its Jordan Brand subsidiary.⁠

@hypebeastkicks: Continuing to celebrate the lunar Year of the Rabbit, @jumpman23 has introduced a new iteration of the Air Jordan 1, inspired by @looneytunes character Bugs Bunny.⁠
⁠
Dressed in a mix of white leather, gray suede, and fluffy faux fur, the silhouette nods to Bugs’ likeness. Side Swooshes come in bright orange and a green stem is fixed on the heel to form a carrot shape. The Jumpman logo then adorns the tongue tab and rounding out the look are white midsoles and green rubber outsoles.⁠
⁠
The pair is currently confirmed in grade school sizing for $95 USD and is set to release via @nike and Jordan Brand in the coming months.⁠

Let’s talk gym anxiety 💭

The gym can be a super daunting and overwhelming place, but it doesn’t have to be!! When I first started, I stressed about anything and everything that could go wrong. It took a really long time for me to feel comfortable and confident doing my workouts. 

Here are a few things that genuinely helped me: 

Fake it till you make it: This is my #1!!! If you walk into the gym with badass energy, I promise no one will question it 

Bring a friend: There’s power in numbers, invite someone you feel comfortable with and let it take some pressure off 👯‍♀️ 

Choose a cute outfit: If you look good, you feel good. So buy that new fit and come in with a bang 💃 

Chat to staff: If someone/ something is making you really uncomfortable, find a member of staff. It’s our job to ensure a safe environment for everyone working out 🏋️‍♀️ 

Back yourself!!! You don’t know what you’re capable of until you do ⚡️

Don’t sell yourself short, we all start the same. You’ll be amazed by what you and your body can do 💥 We’ve GOT this!!!!

🇺🇸🇺🇸 Republican Christine Drazan @christine4oregon holds a 2-point lead over Democrat Tina Kotek @tina4oregon in the race for governor in deep-blue Oregon.

Surveying 1161 registered voters from October 18-22 with a margin of error of ± 2.9 percent, the Trafalgar Group poll showed that Christine Drazan holds a minor lead over Tina Kotek – 42 percent to 40 percent – while 13 percent of voters prefer Independent Betsy Johnson. Drazan’s lead inarguably stems from Betsy Johnson splitting the vote and overall dissatisfaction with crime in the state, given that the city of Portland has often been a hotbed of Antifa rioting. Nike @nike co-founder Phil Knight has also come out strongly for Drazan by donating $1 million to her campaign. A recent Oregon Public Broadcasting poll also found that voters in the state were deeply unhappy with the leadership of Democrat Gov. Kate Brown. President Joe Biden’s incredibly low approval rating has also been a contributing factor in Republicans polling well in various states.

⁠
Expect the kicks to release at the end of the year via Nike and select retailers for $160 USD.⁠

#LebronJames says #KyrieIrving 'caused some harm to a lot of people' for posting dvd that upset j*wish people

“I believe that what Kyrie did caused some harm to a lot of people,” James said after the Lakers lost 130-116 to the Utah Jazz on Friday, adding that he can't speak for why most of the league hasn't spoken against Irving.

After almost a week of doubling down and choosing not to apologize for sharing the documentary or his subsequent media comments, consequences have piled up for Irving. In addition to a five-game suspension without pay from the Brooklyn Nets, Irving's relationship with Nike has been suspended, the company announced Friday.

“He apologized. But he caused some harm and I think it’s unfortunate," James said. "But I don’t stand on the position to harm people when it comes to your voice or your platform or anything. So it doesn’t matter what color your skin is, how tall you are, what position you’re in. If you are promoting or soliciting or saying harmful things to any community that harms people, then I don’t respect it. I don’t condone it.”

5 Things we’ve noticed at the World Cup so far 🔍

1. The patches on the USA shirt being so high up towards the shoulder due to the Nike Swoosh and sleeve detail.

2. The Germany match detail being above the manufacturer logo, not something you see very often. Also Germany don’t seem to be wearing the Adidas World Cup print.

3. Long sleeve glory. A few players are keeping long sleeves alive especially in the Adidas shirts.

4. Denmark wearing a huge flag in the centre of their shirt. There hasn’t been an official explanation as to why though.

@hypebeastuk: From conflict to collaborators: the time @nike sued @crtz.rtw.⁠
⁠
London’s very own streetwear titan Corteiz has officially confirmed its forthcoming collaboration with Nike, taking to Central London’s Oxford Circus to announce the partnership last night.⁠
⁠
While Corteiz’s cult following saluted their first collaboration with a major brand, they may not know their relationship with the Swoosh hasn’t always been sweet.⁠
⁠
The news immediately put streetwear fanatics across the globe into a frenzy in hopes of copping the collaboration once it drops, but many fans may not be aware Nike once filed a lawsuit against Corteiz owner @clint419 in 2021.⁠
⁠
Legal action was cataloged due to the Corteiz name and its uncanny resemblance to one of Nike’s most famous product lines: the Cortez sneaker.⁠
⁠
The case argued that the words Cortez and Corteiz could be confused amongst consumers, causing issues in the market when being wrongfully identified as the same brand or product. The acting judge ordered Corteiz to pay Nike a total sum of £1,850 GBP on March 16, 2021.⁠
⁠
The upcoming team-up means that all past conflict has been left behind, signifying a new era for both brands — with Clint turning a light L into a massive W in just a few years of hard work. The collaboration will see them unite on shared grounds, bringing together two giants in the fashion space to deliver something never seen before.⁠

On Sunday, Tiffany & Co. and Nike took out a full-page print ad in The New York Times featuring a Nike shoe box in Tiffany’s signature robin’s-egg blue, tagged with the logos of both brands and the line: “A Legendary Pair.” By Monday morning, images of the sneakers themselves had “leaked” on social media but I struggled to find a single individual who thought the shoes lived up to the “legendary” label touted in the ads, writes Christopher Morency.⁠
⁠
“I expected so much more than this. This is a no. Take it back to the studio,” said one top commenter on Tiffany’s Instagram. Others chimed in: “They’re not bad if you don’t look at them,” “Is this a joke” and “Just Don’t Do It.” ⁠
⁠
The internet seemed to have made up its mind: the collaboration was nothing more than a marketing play that lacked substance. The lesson? Cultural credibility cannot be bought. And it certainly can’t be reduced to a tired marketing template, argues Morency.⁠
⁠
Read Christopher Morency's op-ed on why he thinks cultural credibility must be earned with respect for sneakerheads, not on their backs. [Link in bio] ⁠

 The propagation speed of sound changes according to the temperature and density of the air.  The speed of sound decreases in cold weather.  Sound changes the direction of propagation as it passes from warm air to cold air.

 In any area, if the wind blows from behind, the sound will be directed towards the ground.  If the wind is blowing from the front, the sound is directed upwards from the ground.  During the day, as the ground heats up, the sound waves head upwards due to the heat effect.  At night, as the ground cools, the sound waves will travel farther and point downwards.

In this case, the wave propagates into a conical area like a beam and is called shock waves.  The ratio of the speed of an object to the speed of sound in that medium is called the Mach number. So, last Sunday, I took part in my first ever half marathon.

From the outside looking in, this may seem like an odd thing to do (as a bodybuilder  with ZERO distance running background lol) BUT if you know me, you know I love pushing my limits & challenging myself. I love seeing where I can take my body & throwing myself into the unfamiliar.

My starting point did not deter me from trying & I committed to see it through. It was also the same day as my Mom's 3 Years - and I wanted to honor her. She fought a long, hard battle with Duodenal cancer - and regardless of this battle, showed up every day with resilience, energy, presence and GRACE. 

Her refusal to give up, showing up everyday with a smile and so much hope - even in the face of so much uncertainty and NO guarantees - changed my perception on life. If you can meet a situation like that, where you are allowed to have EVERY excuse, with none - then I too, have none.

Over the last 12 weeks with the Aus @nike #ekin team - I learned, I trained, I adapted, and I failed...many times. I kept pushing on, until race day finally was on the horizon.

I can't begin to describe how amazing of an experience it was. Yes, it was tough, gruelling & painful - but it was also incredible, awe inspiring, magical & in some ways cathartic. When you are in the moment, you have to face all those feelings head on. You cannot run away. 

And while I may not have been the fastest - that did not matter to me. My goal was to do it & to finish it! And I did ❤️ And as much as I wish that I had my Mom there with me in person, I know she was there in spirit. I don't think there was a step I took that day where I didn't feel my Mom with me, encouraging me, guiding me, pushing me on. It will be something I cherish forever. I am honoured to be able to honor her every day of my life. 

This is your sign to try something new, step outside your comfort zone and never give up. There are boundless experiences waiting for you. There is so much to learn, to live, and to grow from. It's what you make of it that counts.

I want to thank @nikerunning and @melbmara for such an amazing event. I will never forget it and cannot wait for the next one ❤️

@hypebeastkicks: For @jumpman23, themes such as equality have played a key role in various colorways, events, and initiatives throughout each year. In continuation of this, Jordan Brand has now presented the Air Jordan 1 Low “Unity.”⁠
⁠
Landing in a lavender and off-white color scheme, the pair carries unique detailing with its thematic graphics. Looking closer at the sneaker, the toe box reads “Because One Day This Day Will Be Our Everyday” with “Equality” and “Unity” texts on the edges alongside flower and sun doodles in a golden yellow. As for materials, a leather base is joined by rough suede at the mudguard, lacing system, and heel while corduroy hits the collar and tongue. To complete the look, various shades of purple cover the Swoosh and toe box while the laces and midsole get covered in off-white.⁠
⁠
Look for the kicks to release via @nike and select retailers worldwide in the coming months.⁠

@hypebeastuk: Fresh from becoming the NBA’s highest-ever point scorer, @kingjames and @liverpoolfc have officially given the world a first glimpse at their @nike football and basketball jersey collaboration.⁠
⁠
LeBron has been an owner of a minority stake in Liverpool since 2011 and since signing the contract, the athlete has stepped out in an assemblage of different Nike x Liverpool sneaker iterations and colorways. Recently, the LA Lakers star has been seen donning the Air Max 1 “Liverpool” on his way into games, alongside a new collaborative Liverpool FC LeBron 20 silhouette on-court.⁠
⁠
Now, Liverpool FC has unveiled a duo of football and basketball jerseys, with Liverpool’s classic “You’ll Never Walk Alone” slogan arriving on the basketball jersey, while LeBron's own logo features in the sponsor slot on the football shirt.⁠
⁠
This is the duo's first-ever full collaboration since LeBron became a part of the Liverpool family, with the basketball jersey also notably featuring 'YNWA' pinstripe detailing, the GOAT’s favored number, '6' on the back, while a 'Strive For Greatness' slogan sign-off features above.⁠
⁠
You can take a closer look at the collaboration above and be sure to keep an eye on Liverpool's official Instagram page for further release details.⁠
Photo: Liverpool FC

___________________________________________ 
Neighbors, following the one-year anniversary of Virgil Abloh’s death, for the first time ever, his widow, Shannon Abloh, spoke out in a public interview. 
___________________________________________ 
In an interview with the New York Times, Shannon reveals her own plans to shape the legacy of Virgil Abloh. “It’s like this train that’s going 500 miles per hour, and I just thought: I have to stay on this train, because if I don’t, I don’t know where it’s going to go. That’s my place and my position. I think that it’s important that my kids are able to see in 20 years what their dad was able to do and that Mom really stepped up,” she said. “Through everything, through all the grief, I was able to pull it together and move forward… I knew every inch of him. I knew every inch of his brain,” She added.
___________________________________________ 
This year, Shannon founded Virgil Abloh Securities: an umbrella company that binds together all of her husband’s creative ventures, London creative studio, and a joint project with Nike, called Architecture. Then there‘s the four-day music festival at Art Basil, which starts this week and plays host to various discussions, workshops, and exhibitions. There, VA securities will unveil the Nike Air Terra Forma, which is just one of hundreds of unreleased styles yet to surface in a security project that will last 50 years, according to Shannon’s business partner, Howard Feller. 
___________________________________________ 
“Even though we knew the challenge of what he was fighting, it went a lot faster than we thought it was going to," Shannon said. "So we never had the ‘this is the legacy that I want you to work toward' discussion. But because I was with him for so long, I knew every inch of him. I knew every inch of his brain,” Shannon said.
___________________________________________

This year as a part of Union’s ongoing relationship with Brand Jordan we are proud to introduce the first ever AJKO Low 1. The minute I saw this shoe I was immediately transported to my youth in the late 80’s when I would see my favorite rappers in magazines and on album covers rocking those clean looks. I consider this era the prehistory of the modern sneaker culture and to me this is where the foundations of this culture were laid and this AJKO Low 1 felt like it belonged to that era. An “instant classic”.  So in designing Union’s take on this we wanted to lean into this time and really appreciate the simplicity of the shoe. We departed from our usual “disruptive nature” of shoe design and made some much more classic in order to highlight the indelible nature of this sneaker. 

The AJKO 1 Low pays homage to the original AJKO hi sneaker that was originally released in 1986.  What I am most excited about with this shoe is that it offers a new option for Brand Jordan fans in a low top version.  I feel strongly that this design will be an instant classic and can be worn as an everyday shoe much like the Nike AF 1 low.

Light Taupe pebbled leather upper with suede accents on the toe box and eye stay.   Cotton twill tape binding around the seems and the tongue is half leather, half suede with an antique yellow sole. The swoosh is a thick smooth suede and the back tab of the shoe has the AJKO “wings” logo.  Swoosh colors for the leather shoe are Navy and Mint Green. - Chris Gibbs #UNIONAJKO1LOW

@hypebeastkicks: Following initial images earlier this month, we now have an on-foot look at the upcoming @nikesb Dunk Low Decon “N7.”⁠
⁠
Influenced by the Native American wisdom of the seven generations, the N7 project celebrates this rich heritage with various thematic footwear. With this in mind, the sneaker opts for a deconstructed take which sees exposed stitching running across its overlays and Swooshes. Colorful graphics of birds and flowers then break up the otherwise black and white upper. In addition, Nike SB and @nike N7 branding hit the heel in a red embroidery and sockliner in a red print. In the sun-soaked paradise of Montego Bay, Jamaica, during the legendary 1978 WCT Challenge Cup, we caught Björn Borg and John McEnroe in a photo that screams "Please take me back to that era!" 💣
I may have already shared this gem, but it's so good that it's worth the rerun, especially today as we celebrate Björn Borg's 67th birthday! 🎾

Björn Borg is undeniably a true tennis legend. From 1974 to 1981, he made history as the first man in the Open Era to win an impressive total of 11 Grand Slam singles titles. Among them, he triumphed six times at the French Open and five consecutive times at Wimbledon. Despite his remarkable achievements, he narrowly missed claiming victory at the US Open, finishing as a runner-up on four occasions.
And who was his nemesis in two of those finals? None other than the fiery John McEnroe, igniting a rivalry that still sets tennis fans' hearts ablaze. Their clash in the 1980 Wimbledon final is particularly memorable, hailed as one of the most epic matches ever played (which Borg emerged victorious from). Interestingly, Borg and McEnroe have remained close friends throughout the years.

Borg's career took off when he was a teenage sensation, and he experienced unparalleled fame and consistent success, playing a pivotal role in boosting the popularity of tennis during the 1970s.
He graced the covers of gossip magazines as frequently as he did tennis courts, with his romantic life and business endeavors post-retirement ensuring that he never had a dull moment.

Currently, he's taken up residence in his own central Stockholm apartment, living the good life. Happy birthday, champ! 🏆

📸 Jacob Forsell

The Lockheed Martin SR-72, colloquially referred to as "Son of Blackbird", is an American hypersonic UAV concept intended for intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance (ISR) proposed privately in 2013 by Lockheed Martin as a successor to the retired Lockheed SR-71 Blackbird. The company expected an SR-72 test vehicle could fly by 2025.

In June 2017, Lockheed Martin announced that the SR-72 would be in development by the early 2020s, with top speed in excess of Mach 6. Executive Vice President Rob Weiss commented that "We've been saying hypersonics [are] two years away for the last 20 years, but all I can say is the technology is mature and we, along with DARPA and the services, are working hard to get that capability into the hands of our warfighters as soon as possible."

In January 2018, Lockheed Vice President Jack O'Banion gave a presentation that credited the advancements in additive manufacturing and computer modeling, stating that it would not have been possible to make the airplane five years ago and that 3D printing allowed a cooling system to be embedded in the engine.[21][22]

In February 2018, Orlando Carvalho, Executive Vice President of aeronautics at Lockheed Martin, pushed back on reports of the SR-72's development stating that no SR-72 had been produced. He also clarified that hypersonic research is fueling weapons systems development, and that "Eventually as that technology is matured, it could ultimately enable the development of a reusable vehicle. Prior to this we may have referred to it as a "like an SR-72", but now the terminology of choice is "reusable vehicle".

In November 2018, Lockheed Martin stated that a prototype of the SR-72 was scheduled to fly by 2025. The aircraft is to be capable of firing hypersonic missiles.The SR-72 could enter service in the 2030s.

The Supreme x Nike Air Force 1 Low “Box Logo White” takes a less-is-more approach in design and is part of the “World Famous” streetwear brand’s Spring/Summer 2020 collaboration with Nike. Supreme tones down the use of aggressive branding and instead opts for a simple and subtle design, featuring the iconic red Box Logo on the heel of a standard white-on-white Air Force 1 Low. A silver “AF1” emblem covers the bottom of the laces near the perforated toe, while tonal Nike Air branding on the tongue tab and heel complete the look.

Available in-store and online.

Description:
We’re just 26 months in. 

Launched @activelyblack out of my apartment. 

By the time they figure out what we are really building it will be too late. 

We are NOT building an apparel brand. 

The clothes are just the uniform for the movement. 

Thanks @cnbc @cnbcmakeit for the feature story. 

That valuation is from 2021. Put a multiple on it. We are coming for everything our people deserve. 

For the record, we are NOT anti-Nike, anti-Adidas, or anti-ANYBODY. We are just PRO-Actively Black. 

This multi-billion dollar industry lacks Black ownership and true representation in the boardroom and the behind the scenes talent. 

Everybody is welcome to wear @activelyblack regardless of race, color, background… as long as you know the purpose and mission for this brand is to re-invest into and uplift the Black community. 

This is still the beginning. We have a long way to go. But we wouldn’t even be in this position if it wasn’t for the TRIBE and how you all have supported us from the beginning. 

Thank you Tribe for joining us on this journey. 

My love and gratitude to you all. 

- @l.smith23 , Founder. 

Ps. Do y’all think this will finally get some of our people to stop saying we are not Black owned? 😂 

#ActivelyBlack #BlackHistory #ToGodBeTheGlory #PowerToThePeople #ThereIsGreatnessInOurDNA

Description: I just want to take a moment to take a long, hard look back and what has happened over the last ten years. I think if you would take a peek at my instagram and see the highlight reel and think it might’ve been easy - but.. from where ive started (like in the early years of my life).. growing up my dad was homeless and my mom was mentally ill - I spent a lot of time in and out of the system from an early age from central juvenile hall to many years spent in the county - I decided to create a clothing brand while the last time I was incarcerated - I cooked up bxr while I was in the hole at supermax (idk if anyone who is reading this has been there but if you’ve ever eaten juke balls for a month you know the deal). A couple years after working on bxr we started moving, things were great and one month after we launched with union I was diagnosed with terminal cancer (YES, TERMINAL) so from 2013 until now I’ve been battling cancer, did 4 years of chemo lost 100 lbs and my hair numerous times - what I’m getting at is life is hard for everyone and I want anyone to know, that if you’re feeling discouraged or like life has given you too many handicaps - ITS OKAY. you’re going to be fine things will get better. I’m cancer free, I’m not incarcerated and my family has a house to live in and I want to look back at all that has happened and say THANK YOU - because just 5 years ago I was in the worst place in life I’ve ever been and just this last week I’ve been in Vogue, NY Times and a bunch of other places that I am extremely grateful for. If you would have told me 10 years ago I would be hosting a dinner with Nike on the roof of Soho house for 100 of my friends I would’ve never believed you. So I again want to look at all the beautiful gifts life has given me and enjoy all of it. Thank you so much @sohohousecalifornia and @seulgiburns and Nike and @step0nme, my friend @eric.intl for making me this beautiful suit and to my dear friend Lionel Thundercloud @thundercloudjewelry for hand making me all these beautiful pieces I’m wearing my beautiful wife Anna for supporting me and @_carlosjaramillo_ for taking this beautiful photo of me. I have a lot to be thankful for this year.

Nike has suspended its relationship with Brooklyn Nets star Kyrie Irving in the wake of the controversy surrounding his social-media post about a book and movie containing antisemitic ideas, the company announced Friday night.

Nike also said it will no longer launch Irving's new shoe, the Kyrie 8.

"At Nike, we believe there is no place for hate speech and we condemn any form of antisemitism," Nike said in a prepared statement. "We are deeply saddened and disappointed by the situation and its impact on everyone."

Irving was suspended by the Nets on Thursday night for at least five games without pay after failing to formally apologize for his post and failing to clarify whether he held antisemitic beliefs.

Irving apologized in an Instagram post later that night, writing in part: "To All Jewish families and Communities that are hurt and affected from my post, I am deeply sorry to have caused you pain and I apologize."

Irving, 30, has had a lucrative signature series with Nike since 2014.

One year ago today… Hamburg Marathon 😮‍💨🏃🏽‍♂️

Standing at the starting line, realizing that I haven’t trained at all.
Not an ideal situation but that’s what I’ve signed up for. 😂

The question is, are you willing to go where it might hurt a little bit or even a whole lot?!

I wanted to find out and let me tell you it hurt a lot. Definitely the most pain I have ever felt. 

But running those 42km in just under 4 hours, was by far one of the best days of my life. 

It was a journey that I shared with one of my dearest friends. Getting support from start to finish is something I’ll never forget. @maxxbec 

This spring, in about three weeks, I’ll be standing in Copenhagen (hopefully sunny weather) again trying to finish this race. Not a race only for myself, but also for my mate, who is on his own journey this time. 
This time I’ll be the water bottle and pep talk guy. 

For those who are running today in Hamburg. 
I hope you’re nearly there and, even if not, enjoy the pain, the crowd and beautiful weather. 

And for those like me that say “I hate running”, just sign up and do it. 

It will be a challenge of a lifetime but worth the pain… I promise 🫶🏽🏃🏽‍♂️

Description:
Odell Beckham Jr. reportedly will seek an NFL contract worth a prorated $20 million for the balance of the season. He wants the full $20 million, and more, from Nike.

Via TMZ.com, Beckham sued Nike for more than $20 million. The problem traces to a decision by Nike to exercise a right of first refusal in 2017, matching an offer Beckham received from Adidas. Then, in 2022, Nike allegedly began to withhold money from Beckham based on alleged technical violations of his agreement via the footwear and gloves he used in games.

Beckham alleges, among other things, that Nike failed to pay more than $2 million that was due in March 2022.

Beckham has issued a statement on Twitter regarding the situation. He says that he’s pursuing the action to “set a precedent” that will protect other athletes from contractual shenanigans.

While the facts remain to be determined, it’s not crazy to think that Nike regrets a deal done at the height of his popularity. Since 2017, Beckham hasn’t had quite the same sizzle that he did early in his career.

So it’s entirely possible that Nike developed remorse, and that Nike decided to aggressively rely on fine print in the contract.

If Beckham’s rights are being violated, he should be taking action. And if other players have their rights violated by their shoe and apparel partners, they should take action, too. The Nikes of the world don’t hesitate to mobilize the lawyers whenever their rights are compromised, in any way. Players shouldn’t hesitate, either.

Blogged by: @CachéRoberts⁠
⁠
#Netflix is trying to give its viewers a hint by telling them to stop binge-watching and get to working out. The streaming platform is now doing an aerobics workout class.⁠
⁠
The streaming platform is partnering up with #NikeTrainingClub to release 30 hours of sessions across two parts on December 30. This isn’t the first time that Netflix has ventured outside its reigns. In November, the streaming house introduced #TriviaQuest for users to brush up on art, history, entertainment, and more.⁠
⁠
The workout videos come just in time for the #NewYear to help watchers achieve their resolutions, and it’s right after Christmas when everyone will be indulging in more food.⁠
⁠
The first five programs include “Kickstart Fitness with the Basics” (13 episodes), “Two Weeks to a Stronger Core” (seven episodes), “Fall in Love with Vinyasa” (six episodes), “HIT & Strength with Tara” (14 episodes), “Feel-Good Fitness” (six episodes which will be available on Dec. 30…to read the rest log on to BallerAlert.com (clickable link on profile).⁠

@aik further consolidate their position as one of the sharpest clubs in football with the reveal of their upcoming special edition kit for 2023. This year, together with partner Nike, they take this to a new level with the AIK Stockholm Edition Cup Kit, which pays tribute to the home city. On the chest, we see a pattern inspired by the Sun Table, an oil painting from the sixteenth century which is one of the oldest known depictions of Stockholm. The raised marks on the shirt are handcrafted and made in 3D silicone to bring out the highest possible richness of detail. The club badge also has a fabric base in black velvet. All the gold details on the shirt have been enriched with metal particles for a more prominent gold shimmer.

Nike KD 15 "Aunt Pearl"

Every year a new KD model comes out, and every year we all wait for this colorway. No doubt it is one of the coolest KD colorway that is carried on every model. The Aunt Pearl colorway  has always been a signature KD cw. The way it is done here on the KD15 is 🔥.

It comes with a lightweight multi-layer fabric upper done in light pink. It has a light pink fuse overlay on the toebox.The midfoot cage is done in light pink TPU material. Both sides have pink stained glass swoosh logos whose pattern is similar to the KD5 Aunt Pearl and KD12 Aunt Pearl insole. Tongue comes in pink fabric with stitching. The KD logo on the tongue comes in light pink emroidered patch. Laces come in light pink as well.  Ankle and heel area comes in light pink suede with a rose white stitching. Pull tab comes in a darker pink with white rose embroidery.

Midsole comes in light pink. For cushion it uses full length Zoom Air Strobel.

Outsole comes in translucent pink rubber.

One of the cleanest Aunt Pearl for me.

@hypebeastkicks: @maniere_usa and @jumpman23 have built a strong relationship over the years releasing a number of projects that arrived in the form of the Air Jordan 1, 2, and 3. Now it's only right to continue that legacy with an official look at the Jordan 4 iteration.⁠
⁠
A dusted “Violet Ore” hue is used in high quantity here as it submerges the side panels, tongues, netted throats and quarters, laces, cages, overlays and interior quilted liners. Extra AMM branding is present through an oversized “A” that lands on the left tongue and a button that is planted into the collars. ⁠
⁠
Inspirational messaging also gets tossed into the mix here on the insides of the heel counters. The right shoe reads “It’s not about the shoes” while the left shoe says “It’s about where you’re going.” To top everything off, A Ma Maniére brandishes the heel counters with the more favorable “Nike Air” hits. The shoe is expected to release on November 23.⁠

The unfortunate thing here is that most people have no idea their shoes are actively deforming their feet. Slowly over time the foot begins to adapt to the shape of the shoe without you even realizing it (many shoes today are WAYYY too narrow in the toe box). This happens with almost every “popular” shoe brand in the world (Nike, Adidas, etc). 

The most noticeable difference is in the toe position. The angled position of the toes in the top shoe is called “toe spring.” If you closely examine many of your shoes (especially those designed for athletics) the front tip will be elevated a few degrees. Originally this feature was built into thick and inflexible shoes as a way to help “roll” the foot forward as you walk. Think about this as having the bottom of a rocking chair on your foot.
.
So why is this a problem?
.
Toe spring basically forces the toes of your foot “out of business.” Your foot was designed to have all of your toes completely flat on the ground when weightbearing. This allows the toes to grasp the ground and provide stability for the entire foot and therefore the rest of the body. Because 18 of the foot’s 19 tendons are attached to the toes, allowing them to remain flat essentially anchors your entire foot to the ground and enhances stability (one reason why toe spring on a weightlifting shoe or any shoes you wear to the gym makes absolutely zero functional sense).

When it comes to athletic footwear, many of us have been taught to find shoes that have a “snug fit” based on the idea the foot needs more support. However, when it comes to the toes, this notion couldn’t be further from the truth. A narrow fitting toe box hinders the natural and desirable expansion of the foot (called toe splay) that should happen when weightbearing. Without toe splay the foot cannot functional naturally within the shoe and provide optimal stability for the rest of the body.

So what do we do now? We try to find shoes that are wide at the toebox to allow our toes to spread out.

We also remain barefoot as much as possible with our feet connected to the earth. 

The introduction of rubber sole synthetic shoes into our lives has done more harm than you can imagine.

Bit of a different post from me this time (TW)
On Tuesday this week I was told I have a partially bulged disc in my lower back. Immediately I felt like I was drowning in anxiety and stress due to the fact that this injury means my training has to take a back seat for a while. 
As someone who has struggled with eating disorders and body image issues from a very young age, not training is something I don’t deal with very well. 
I immediately began to spiral into thinking I’m going to lose all the progress I’ve made over the last 3 years (I know this isn’t true but you can’t help but think it) 
I’m looking in the mirror and hating what I see when realistically I know nothing much has changed. 
I wanted to share this because my Instagram is a representation of when things in my life are really good- however, I want to be more open about when things are bad. 
Some of you may think ‘you’ve just injured your back, it’s not that deep.’ But training is such a big part of my life physically and mentally and taking that away is really challenging. 
So, I just wanted to say if you’ve ever felt this way about how you look and the way you think about yourself or view yourself, just know you’re absolutely not alone. We all have bad days so I thought I’d share mine with you 

(Also I know the pic doesn’t exactly match the post but I don’t feel good at the moment and wanted to use a pic that did make me feel good)

Almost two years later, @Nike came through in the clutch 🙌

@hypebeastkicks: By now, many of our rotations consist of Air Jordan 1s, Dunks, Blazers, Air Maxs, and the many re-retros. Now @nike is looking to focus on "breakthrough innovation" as the current product lineup is becoming "stale."⁠
⁠
The Swoosh is making executive changes in hopes to supercharge product development. With recent shifts in the sneaker industry, what was once a coveted Air Jordan 1 fetching profitable returns in the aftermarket has now become overstock due to saturated colorways and the same old retros which some are now selling for under retail.⁠
⁠
President & CEO, NIKE, Inc John Donahoe stated: ⁠
⁠
“These shifts will allow us to streamline our focus across product, brand storytelling and marketplace, mining deep consumer insights to deliver breakthrough innovation and engagement, while building long-term growth and profitability.”⁠
⁠
Photo: Hypebeast
